# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: horseley-ironworks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby was born at Albrighton, Shropshire on 15 November 1776 to Aaron Manby of Kingston, Jamaica and Jane Lane of Bentley.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] They had a son, Charles Manby, who became Secretary of the Institution of Civil Engineers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1807 Manby married Sarah Ann Haskins, with whom he had one daughter, Sarah Maria (d.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The oldest three of them, John Richard (1813-1869), Joseph Lane (1814-1862), and Edward Oliver (1816-1864), also became civil engineers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's working life was originally in banks on the Isle of Wight.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1812 Manby was managing partner of the Horseley Coal and Iron Co, Tipton, Staffordshire.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] It ran coal mines, blast furnaces to make iron, and assorted workshops.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby expanded the business into civil engineering.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1813 Manby obtained patent No 3705 for a means of casting the slag from blast furnaces into blocks for building.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1815, the firm supplied a cast-iron swing bridge, possibly the first of Horseley's many iron bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1821, diversifying into mechanical engineering, Manby obtained British Patent No 4558 for his "oscillating engine" designed for use in ships.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] That same year, Horseley Ironworks constructed the world's first seagoing iron steamboat, named the *Aaron Manby*, using his oscillating engine.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] The boat was built at Tipton using temporary bolts, disassembled for transportation to London, and reassembled on the Thames in 1822, this time using permanent rivets.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Between 1819 and 1822, Manby started his engineering works at Charenton-le-Pont, near Paris, with the Scottish chemist Daniel Wilson as manager.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] This controversial move enabled France to stop buying engines made in England, which made Manby somewhat unpopular.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1822 Manby and Wilson's *Compagnie d'Éclairage par de Gaz Hydrogène* ('Hydrogen Gas Lighting Company') was granted the right to provide gas lighting for several streets in Paris.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] According to Michel Cotte, "The company Manby & Wilson is certainly the largest company of British origin which set up in France under the Restoration." Their *"Compagnie Anglaise"* ran until 1847, expanding to take in the Le Creusot ironworks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] Manby's Horseley Ironworks profited from the growing canal trade, manufacturing canal bridges in the English Midlands including the Engine Arm Aqueduct (1825) and two roving bridges at Smethwick Junction (1828).
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] In 1845 Manby sold Horseley Ironworks to John Joseph Bramah (~1798 - 1846), nephew of the inventor and locksmith Joseph Bramah.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby-ironmaster] After returning from France in about 1840, he lived at Fulham, London, before retiring to the Isle of Wight where he died.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] Launched in 1821, *Aaron Manby* was the first steamship to be built of iron.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] She was the brainchild of the eccentric but far-seeing naval officer Captain (later Admiral) Charles Napier, who had conceived the idea of a fleet of steamships for service on the River Seine.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] The ship was named after the master of the Horseley Ironworks, Tipton, Staffordshire, where she was pre-fabricated to a design jointly formulated by Captain Napier, Aaron Manby and his son Charles.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] She was then shipped in pieces to Rotherhithe on the Thames and assembled there.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] Of 116 tons burthen, the ship was 120 feet (37 m) long.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] Her flat-bottomed hull was made of 1⁄4-inch-thick (6.4 mm) iron plate fastened to angle-iron ribs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] There was one deck, of wood, and a bowsprit.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] The ship's distinctive profile boasted a single 47-foot-high (14 m) funnel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] The engine was of the oscillating type, designed and patented (British Patent No 4558 of 1821) by Aaron Manby.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] The paddlewheels: were 12 feet (3.7 m) in diameter but only 2.5 feet (76 cm) wide, because the vessel's maximum beam was limited to 23 feet (7.0 m) for service on the Seine.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] Defying the prevailing wisdom of the day, the iron-hulled vessel not only floated but made 9 knots (10 mph; 17 km/h) and drew one foot (30 cm) less water than any other steamboat then operating.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] After trials in May 1822, *Aaron Manby* crossed the English Channel to Le Havre under Napier's command on 10 June, at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h), carrying passengers and freighted with a cargo of linseed and iron castings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] The ship proceeded up the Seine to Paris, where she caused a great stir and where she was based for the next decade.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] This has been claimed (incorrectly) as the first passage from Britain to France by steam ship.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] There had been shorter crossings by wooden steamers, but Napier's was the first direct steam crossing from London to Paris and the first seagoing voyage by an iron ship anywhere.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] After some further channel voyages the ship was used for pleasure trips up and down the Seine.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] The use of iron plates for the hull, in place of wood, was widely copied in shipbuilding during the following decades.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aaron-manby] Napier had conceived the ship as a first step towards an iron warship, and in this sense *Aaron Manby* could be considered a direct ancestor of the Royal Navy's first iron frigate, HMS *Warrior*, built the year of Napier's death.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] The Atherstone to Fradley link would connect with the end of the Birmingham and Fazeley at Fazeley Junction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] The company wanted to ensure that the canal would be part of a larger network, once completed, that would carry trade to London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] The canal was completed from Farmers Bridge Junction, in the heart of Birmingham, to Fazeley in 1789, and the connecting links were completed in the following year.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] Shortly after the passing of the act, the Birmingham and Fazeley Canal merged with the Birmingham Canal Company and eventually became known as the Birmingham Canal Navigations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] The Digbeth Branch, which joined the original Birmingham and Fazeley line at Aston Junction, was built using the powers of the Birmingham Canal Navigation Act 1768 (8 Geo.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] 38), although the work was not undertaken until 1799.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] It was a short branch with six locks, which terminated at Typhoo Basin.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] Just before the end of the branch was a junction with the Warwick and Birmingham Canal, which became part of the Grand Union Canal following amalgamations in 1929.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] The junction was increasingly congested, as it was the main link between the Birmingham Canal network and the Warwick and Birmingham Canal route to London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] Travel in any direction from the junction involved a flight of locks, and options to bypass the Farmers Bridge locks had been under consideration since 1793.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] Instead, the Garrison flight on the new line had just five locks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] From the junction, the Birmingham and Fazeley Canal heads to the south-west and ascends through the 13 Farmers Bridge locks, rising 81 feet (25 m) to reach Farmers Bridge Junction, 1.3 miles (2.1 km) away.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] To the north-east, it descends through the eleven locks of the Aston flight, to reach Salford junction, 1.8 miles (2.9 km) away, where it is joined by the Tame Valley Canal and the Grand Union Canal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] The Digbeth Branch heads south-east, and is just 0.9 miles (1.4 km) long.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] Typhoo Basin is also known as Digbeth Basin or Bordesley Basin.
[src:horseley-ironworks/aston-junction] Aston Junction is notable in having two bridges serving the same lock; an iron Horseley bridge at the top and a brick bridge at the bottom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The **BCN Main Line**, or **Birmingham Canal Navigations Main Line** is the evolving route of the **Birmingham Canal** between Birmingham and Wolverhampton in England.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The name *Main Line* was used to distinguish the main Birmingham to Wolverhampton route from the many other canals and branches built or acquired by the Birmingham Canal Navigations company.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] They commissioned the canal engineer James Brindley to propose a route.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Brindley came back with a largely level but meandering route via Smethwick, Oldbury, Tipton, Bilston and Wolverhampton to Aldersley.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] On 24 February 1768, an Act of Parliament was passed to allow the building of the canal, with branches at Ocker Hill and Wednesbury where there were coal mines.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Staffordshire and Worcestershire company was given the right to make the connection to their canal if the Birmingham company failed to do so within six months of opening.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] On 2 March Brindley was appointed engineer.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The first phase of building was to Wednesbury whereupon the price of coal sold to domestic households in Birmingham halved overnight.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Vested interests of the sponsors caused the creation of two terminal wharves in Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The 1772 Newhall Branch and wharf (now built upon) originally extended north of, and parallel to Great Charles Street.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The 1773 Paradise Street Branch split off at Old Turn Junction and headed through Broad Street Tunnel, turned left at what is now Gas Street Basin and under Bridge Street to wharves on a tuning fork-shaped pair of long basins: Paradise Wharf, also called Old Wharf.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Birmingham Canal Company head office was finally built there, opposite the western end of Paradise Street.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] By 6 November 1769, 10 miles (16 km) had been completed to Hill Top collieries in West Bromwich, with a one-mile summit pound at Smethwick.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Brindley had tried to dig a tunnel through the hill at Smethwick but had encountered ground too soft to cope with.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The canal rose from what is now the Birmingham Level through six narrow (7 ft, 2.1 m) locks to the summit level and descended through another six at Spon Lane.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Water was brought from purpose-built reservoirs: Smethwick Great Reservoir (now built upon, holding 1514 locks of water), another smaller pool at Smethwick (holding 500 locks), and then from Titford Pool to supply the summit level.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In 1770 work started towards Wolverhampton, from above the third Spon Lane lock at what is now the Wolverhampton Level.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] On 21 September 1772 the canal was joined with the Staffordshire and Worcestershire Canal at Aldersley Junction via another 20 locks (increased to 21 in 1784 to save water).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The canal measured 22+5⁄8 miles (36.4 km), mostly following the contour of the land but with deviations to factories and mines in the Black Country and Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] A branch led to Matthew Boulton's Soho Manufactory.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The original Birmingham Canal was extremely successful but there was a problem with supplying sufficient water to the Smethwick Summit.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Matthew Boulton's partner, James Watt, had just patented an improvement to the steam engine involving an external condenser which improved the efficiency (and therefore reduced the amount of coal needed to run it).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Steam engines were constructed at either end of the Smethwick Summit to pump water used in the operation of the locks back to the summit.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Smethwick Engine (5 June 1779) pumped water from the Birmingham side of the summit, and another, the Spon Lane Engine (April 1778) operated from the Wolverhampton side.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] This created an even greater need for water to supply the thirteen locks at Farmer's Bridge and eleven at Aston, all running downhill and taking water out of the Birmingham system.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] There were problems of congestion at Smethwick caused by the time taken to traverse the locks and with supplying sufficient water to the summit level.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] John Smeaton was engaged to advise on a solution.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] He specified a 1000-yard cutting through the top eighteen feet of the summit, eliminating three locks from each end, and doubling the capacity of the descent at Smethwick locks by building a parallel flight of three locks, in use until the 1960s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The changes were made in two phases with a new cut to the side to remove two locks from each end and lower the summit by twelve feet, and then another parallel cut another six feet lower, removing another lock at each end and the provision of a parallel set of three locks at the Smethwick end.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In 1790, after 2+1⁄2 years the cutting was completed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The lowered summit was at the Wolverhampton Level and simplified water supply.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Water was also pumped from several local coal mines.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Spon Lane engine was removed and sold but the Smethwick Engine continued to be used to pump used water from the Birmingham Level.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Act allowed for branches to extend from the main line, and for private wharves and basins.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In May 1821 the loop of the main line around Oldbury was bypassed by a straight cut, shortening the route between Birmingham and Wolverhampton.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Over the next thirty years, as more canals and branches were built or connected it became necessary to review the long, winding, narrow Old Main Line.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] With a single towpath boats passing in opposite directions had to negotiate their horses and ropes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] As traffic grew the locks at Smethwick Summit were still a constriction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In 1824 Thomas Telford was commissioned to examine alternatives.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Telford proposed major changes to the section between Birmingham and Smethwick, widening and straightening the canal, providing towpaths on each side, and cutting through Smethwick Summit to bypass the locks, allowing lock-free passage from Birmingham to Tipton.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Telford's proposals were swayed by the threat of a new Birmingham to Liverpool railway.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] His suggestions were accepted and he was appointed chief engineer on 28 June 1824.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] By 1827 the **New Main Line** passed straight through, and linked to, the loops of the Old Main Line, creating Oozells Loop, Icknield Port Loop, Soho Loop, Cape Loop and Soho Foundry Loop, allowing continued access to the existing factories and wharves.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] A year earlier he had built an improved Rotton Park Reservoir (Edgbaston Reservoir) on the site of an existing fish pool, bringing its capacity to 300 million imperial gallons (1,400,000 m3).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] A canal feeder took water to, and along, a raised embankment on the south side of the New Main Line to his new Engine Arm branch canal and across an elegant cast iron aqueduct to top up the higher Wolverhampton Level at Smethwick Summit.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The reservoir also fed water to the Birmingham Level at the adjacent Icknield Port Loop.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Smethwick Summit was bypassed by 71 ft (22 m) cutting through Lunar Society member, Samuel Galton's land, creating the Galton Valley, 70 feet deep and 150 feet wide, running parallel to the Old Main Line.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Telford's changes here were completed in 1829.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Telford designed a cast iron bridge, the Galton Bridge, to span his cutting.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] It was cast in the Horseley Iron Works, as was the Engine Arm Aqueduct and many of the wide roving bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In 1837, after Telford's death, a new section of his planned canal was opened together with the 360 yard Coseley Tunnel, complete with double towpath, cutting out the long detour around Coseley and Wednesbury Oak, and therefore relegating it as the Wednesbury Oak Loop.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] As with many of the branch canals on the BCN, most of the Wednesbury Oak Loop became officially abandoned from 1954, but the northern stretch remains navigable to the British Waterways workshops at Bradley.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] By 1838 the New Main Line was complete: 22+5⁄8 miles (36.4 km) of slow canal reduced to 15+5⁄8 miles (25.1 km); between Birmingham and Tipton, it was a lock-free dual carriageway.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] It was also called the **Island Line** as it was cut straight through the hill at Smethwick known as the Island.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In 1892 the Smethwick Engine was replaced by a new pumping house between the old and new canals, just north of Brasshouse Lane Bridge in Smethwick.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Late in the 20th century, a pair of concrete tunnels near Galton Bridge were built to carry the Telford Way road.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Ryland Aqueduct, built in 1836 carrying the canal over the main A461 road at Dudley Port, Tipton, was rebuilt in the late 1960s at a cost of £170,000 (equivalent to £2,708,800 in 2025).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] Demolition of the old aqueduct took place in September 1967.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] In 1991 at a cost of £22,000 its bare concrete structure was painted blue and white and included a frieze of a narrowboat crossing an old-fashioned brick aqueduct.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bcn-main-line] The Smethwick Summit - Galton Valley Conservation Area protects the Old and New lines between the Birmingham city boundary and Spon Lane locks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Located in the West Midlands region of England, Birmingham is considered to be the social, cultural, financial and commercial centre of the Midlands.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] It is just west of the traditional centre point of England at Meriden, and is the most inland major city in the country, lying north of the Cotswolds and east of the Shropshire Hills.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Distinctively, Birmingham only has small rivers flowing through it, mainly the River Tame and its tributaries River Rea and River Cole – one of the closest main rivers is the Severn, approximately 20 miles (32 km) west of the city centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city has numerous canals, known as the Birmingham Canal Navigations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By 1791, it was being hailed as "the first manufacturing town in the world".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The resulting high level of social mobility also fostered a culture of political radicalism which, under leaders from Thomas Attwood to Joseph Chamberlain, was to give it a political influence unparalleled in Britain outside London and a pivotal role in the development of British democracy.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] From the summer of 1940 to the spring of 1943, Birmingham was bombed heavily by the German Luftwaffe in what is known as the Birmingham Blitz.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The damage done to the city's infrastructure, in addition to a deliberate policy of demolition and new building by planners, led to extensive urban regeneration in subsequent decades.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham's economy is now dominated by the service sector.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city is a major international commercial centre and an important transport, retail, events and conference hub.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Its metropolitan economy is the second-largest in the United Kingdom with a GDP of £95.94bn (2014).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Its five universities, including the University of Birmingham, make it the largest centre of higher education in the country outside London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham was the host city for the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 2021, Birmingham was the third most visited city in the UK by people from foreign nations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The name *Birmingham* comes from the Old English *Beormingahām*, meaning the home or settlement of the *Beormingas* – a tribe or clan whose name means 'Beorma's people' and which may have formed an early unit of Anglo-Saxon administration.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Beorma, after whom the tribe was named, could have been its leader at the time of the Anglo-Saxon settlement, a shared ancestor, or a mythical tribal figurehead.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Place names ending in *-ingahām* are characteristic of primary settlements established during the early phases of Anglo-Saxon colonisation of an area, suggesting that Birmingham was probably in existence by the early 7th century at the latest.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Surrounding settlements with names ending in *-tūn* ('farm'), *-lēah* ('woodland clearing'), *-worð* ('enclosure') and *-field* ('open ground') are likely to be secondary settlements created by the later expansion of the Anglo-Saxon population, in some cases possibly on earlier British sites.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] There is evidence of early human activity in the Birmingham area dating back to around 8000 BC, with Stone Age artefacts suggesting seasonal settlements, overnight hunting parties and woodland activities such as tree felling.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] During the 1st-century Roman conquest of Britain, the forested country of the Birmingham Plateau formed a barrier to the advancing Roman legions, who built the large Metchley Fort in the area of modern-day Edgbaston in AD 48, and made it the focus of a network of Roman roads.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham was then later established by the *Beormingas* around the 6th or 7th century as a small settlement in the then heavily forested Arden region in Mercia.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This established Birmingham as the primary commercial centre for the Birmingham Plateau at a time when the area's economy was expanding rapidly, with population growth nationally leading to the clearance, cultivation and settlement of previously marginal land.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Within a century of the charter Birmingham had grown into a prosperous urban centre of merchants and craftsmen.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By 1327 it was the third-largest town in Warwickshire, a position it would retain for the next 200 years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The importance of the manufacture of iron goods to Birmingham's economy was recognised as early as 1538, and grew rapidly as the century progressed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Equally significant was the town's emerging role as a centre for the iron merchants who organised finance, supplied raw materials and traded and marketed the industry's products.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By the 1600s Birmingham formed the commercial hub of a network of forges and furnaces stretching from South Wales to Cheshire and its merchants were selling finished manufactured goods as far afield as the West Indies.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] These trading links gave Birmingham's metalworkers access to much wider markets, allowing them to diversify away from lower-skilled trades producing basic goods for local sale, towards a broader range of specialist, higher-skilled and more lucrative activities.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By the time of the English Civil War Birmingham's booming economy, its expanding population, and its resulting high levels of social mobility and cultural pluralism, had seen it develop new social structures very different from those of more established areas.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Relationships were built around pragmatic commercial linkages rather than the rigid paternalism and deference of feudal society, and loyalties to the traditional hierarchies of the established church and aristocracy were weak.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The town's reputation for political radicalism and its strongly Parliamentarian sympathies saw it attacked by Royalist forces in the Battle of Birmingham in 1643, and it developed into a centre of Puritanism in the 1630s and as a haven for Nonconformists from the 1660s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By 1700 Birmingham's population had increased fifteen-fold and the town was the fifth-largest in England and Wales.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The 18th century saw this tradition of free-thinking and collaboration blossom into the cultural phenomenon now known as the Midlands Enlightenment.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This created a "chain reaction of innovation", forming a pivotal link between the earlier Scientific Revolution and the Industrial Revolution that would follow.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham's explosive industrial expansion started earlier than that of the textile-manufacturing towns of the North of England, and was driven by different factors.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This led to exceptional levels of inventiveness: between 1760 and 1850 – the core years of the Industrial Revolution – Birmingham residents registered over three times as many patents as those of any other British town or city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The demand for capital to feed rapid economic expansion also saw Birmingham grow into a major financial and commercial centre with extensive international connections.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Lloyds Bank was founded in the town in 1765, and Ketley's Building Society, the world's first building society, in 1775.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By 1800 the West Midlands had more banking offices per head than any other region in Britain, including London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Innovation in 18th-century Birmingham often took the form of incremental series of small-scale improvements to existing products or processes, but also included major developments that lay at the heart of the emergence of industrial society.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 1709 the Birmingham-trained Abraham Darby I moved to Coalbrookdale in Shropshire and built the first blast furnace to successfully smelt iron ore with coke, transforming the quality, volume and scale on which it was possible to produce cast iron.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 1732 Lewis Paul and John Wyatt invented roller spinning, the "one novel idea of the first importance" in the development of the mechanised cotton industry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 1741 they opened the world's first cotton mill in Birmingham's Upper Priory.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 1746 John Roebuck invented the lead chamber process, enabling the large-scale manufacture of sulphuric acid, and in 1780 James Keir developed a process for the bulk manufacture of alkali, together marking the birth of the modern chemical industry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 1765 Matthew Boulton opened the Soho Manufactory, pioneering the combination and mechanisation under one roof of previously separate manufacturing activities through a system known as "rational manufacture".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] As the largest manufacturing unit in Europe, this came to symbolise the emergence of the factory system.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Most significant, however, was the development in 1776 of the industrial steam engine by James Watt and Matthew Boulton.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Freeing for the first time the manufacturing capacity of human society from the limited availability of hand, water and animal power, this was arguably the pivotal moment of the entire Industrial Revolution and a key factor in the worldwide increases in productivity over the following century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham rose to national political prominence in the campaign for political reform in the early 19th century, with Thomas Attwood and the Birmingham Political Union bringing the country to the brink of civil war during the Days of May that preceded the passing of the Reform Act 1832.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The union's meetings on Newhall Hill in 1831 and 1832 were the largest political assemblies Britain had ever seen.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Lord Durham, who drafted the act, wrote that "the country owed Reform to Birmingham, and its salvation from revolution".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This reputation for having "shaken the fabric of privilege to its base" in 1832 led John Bright to make Birmingham the platform for his successful campaign for the Reform Act 1867, which extended voting rights to the urban working class.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The original charter of incorporation, dated 31 October 1838, was received in Birmingham on 1 November, then read in the town hall on 5 November with elections for the first Birmingham Town Council being held on 26 December.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Sixteen aldermen and 48 councillors were elected and the borough was divided into 13 wards.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] William Scholefield became the first mayor and William Redfern was appointed as town clerk.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham Town Police were established the following year.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham's tradition of innovation continued into the 19th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] By the 1820s, the country's extensive canal system had been constructed, giving greater access to natural resources and fuel for industries.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham was the terminus for both of the world's first two long-distance railway lines: the 82-mile (132 km) Grand Junction Railway of 1837 and the 112-mile (180 km) London and Birmingham Railway of 1838.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham schoolteacher Rowland Hill invented the postage stamp and created the first modern universal postal system in 1839.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Alexander Parkes invented the first human-made plastic in the Jewellery Quarter in 1855.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] During the Victorian era, the population of Birmingham grew rapidly to well over half a million and Birmingham became the second largest population centre in England.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham was granted city status in 1889 by Queen Victoria.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Joseph Chamberlain, mayor of Birmingham and later an MP, and his son Neville Chamberlain, who was Lord Mayor of Birmingham and later the British Prime Minister, are two of the most well-known political figures who have lived in Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city established its own university in 1900.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city suffered heavy bomb damage during World War II's "Birmingham Blitz".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city was also the scene of two scientific discoveries that were to prove critical to the outcome of the war.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Otto Frisch and Rudolf Peierls first described how a practical nuclear weapon could be constructed in the Frisch–Peierls memorandum of 1940, the same year that the cavity magnetron, the key component of radar and later of microwave ovens, was invented by John Randall and Harry Boot.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city was extensively redeveloped during the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This included the construction of large tower block estates, such as Castle Vale.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The Bull Ring was reconstructed and New Street station was redeveloped.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In the decades following World War II, the ethnic makeup of Birmingham changed significantly, as it received waves of immigration from the Commonwealth of Nations and beyond.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city's population peaked in 1951 at 1,113,000 residents.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] 21 people were killed and 182 were injured in a series of bomb attacks in 1974, thought to be carried out by the Provisional IRA.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The bombings were the worst terror attacks in England up until the 2005 London bombings and consisted of bombs being planted in two pubs in central Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Six men were convicted, who became known later as the Birmingham Six and sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] They were acquitted after 16 years by the Court of Appeal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The convictions are now considered one of the worst miscarriages of justice in the UK in recent times.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The true perpetrators of the attacks are yet to be arrested.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] These measures hindered "the natural self-regeneration of businesses in Birmingham, leaving it top-heavy with the old and infirm", and the city became increasingly dependent on the motor industry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The recession of the early 1980s saw Birmingham's economy collapse, with unprecedented levels of unemployment and outbreaks of social unrest in inner-city districts.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 1998 Birmingham hosted the 24th G8 summit.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city successfully hosted the 2022 Commonwealth Games.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham City Council has 104 councillors representing 69 wards as of 2026.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Its headquarters are at the Council House in Victoria Square.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] As of 2026, the council has no overall majority.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] A group of Green, Lib Dem and independent councillors form an administration, which is led by Lib Dem councillor Roger Harmer.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Labour held a majority from the May 2012 elections to May 2026.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The honour and dignity of a Lord Mayoralty was conferred on Birmingham by Letters Patent on 3 June 1896.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham's ten parliamentary constituencies are represented in the House of Commons as of 2024 by one Conservative, one independent and eight Labour MPs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Originally part of Warwickshire, Birmingham expanded in the late 19th and early 20th centuries, absorbing parts of Worcestershire to the south and Staffordshire to the north and west.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city absorbed Sutton Coldfield in 1974 and became a metropolitan borough in the new West Midlands county, comprising Birmingham, Coventry, Dudley, Sandwell, Solihull, Walsall, and Wolverhampton.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] A top-level government body, the West Midlands Combined Authority, was formed in April 2016.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The WMCA holds devolved powers in transport, development planning, economic growth, and large-scale investment.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The authority is governed by a directly elected mayor, currently Labour's Richard Parker, similar to the Mayor of London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] On 5 September 2023, Birmingham city council issued a Section 114 notice to say that it could not meet its financial commitments after an equal pay lawsuit.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Effectively this meant the council was bankrupt.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Major contributing factors include a £1.1 billion sum that has been paid out since 2010 for equal pay claims, an ongoing bill for £760 million, increasing by £14 million a month, and problems with a new IT system that was projected to cost £19 million, but is now closer to £100 million.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] There is a projected £87 million deficit for the financial year 2023/2024.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] To the immediate south west of the city lie the Lickey Hills, Clent Hills and Walton Hill, which reach 1,033 feet (315 m) and have extensive views over the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham is drained only by minor rivers and brooks, primarily the River Tame and its tributaries the Cole and the Rea.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham is located significantly inland, and its nearest body of sea is at Liverpool Bay.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] It lies at the same latitude as Lowestoft, Britain's easternmost settlement; it is therefore much more proximate to the western coast of Wales, at Cardigan Bay.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The City of Birmingham forms a conurbation with the borough of Solihull to the south east, and with the city of Wolverhampton and the industrial towns of the Black Country to the north west, which form the West Midlands Built-up Area covering 59,972 ha (600 km2; 232 sq mi).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] As the crow flies, Birmingham lies approximately 100 miles (160 km) north-west of London, 85 miles (137 km) north-east of the Welsh capital Cardiff, 45 miles (72 km) south-west of Nottingham, 70 miles (110 km) south of Manchester, and 75 miles (121 km) north-north-east of Bristol.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Much of the area now occupied by the city was originally a northern reach of the ancient Forest of Arden and the city remains relatively densely covered by oak in a large number of districts such as Moseley, Saltley, Yardley, Stirchley and Hockley.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] These places, with names ending in "-ley", deriving from Old English *-*lēah** meaning "woodland clearing", are named after the former forest.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham is dominated by the Birmingham Fault, which runs diagonally through the city from the Lickey Hills in the south west, passing through Edgbaston and the Bull Ring, to Erdington and Sutton Coldfield in the north east.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] To the south and east of the fault the ground is largely softer Mercia Mudstone, interspersed with beds of Bunter pebbles and crossed by the valleys of the Rivers Tame, Rea and Cole and their tributaries.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] To the north and west of the fault, between 150 and 600 feet (46 and 183 metres) higher than the surrounding area and underlying much of the city centre, lies a long ridge of harder Keuper Sandstone.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The bedrock underlying Birmingham was mostly laid down during the Permian and Triassic periods.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The area has evidence of glacial deposits, with prominent erratic boulders becoming a tourist attraction in the early 1900s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham has a temperate maritime climate (*Cfb* according to the Köppen climate classification), like much of the British Isles, with average maximum temperatures in summer (July) being about 21.3 °C (70.3 °F); and in winter (January) about 6.7 °C (44.1 °F).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Between 1971 and 2000 the warmest day of the year on average was 28.8 °C (83.8 °F) and the coldest night typically fell to −9.0 °C (15.8 °F).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Some 11.2 days each year rose to a temperature of 25.1 °C (77.2 °F) or above and 51.6 nights reported an air frost.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The highest recorded temperature recorded at the Edgbaston Campus was 37.4 °C (99.3 °F), whilst a temperature of 37.0 °C (98.6 °F) was recorded at Birmingham Airport on the city's eastern edge, both recorded on 19 July 2022.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Like most other large cities, Birmingham has a considerable urban heat island effect.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] During the coldest night recorded, 14 January 1982, the temperature fell to −20.8 °C (−5.4 °F) at Birmingham Airport, but just −14.3 °C (6.3 °F) at Edgbaston, near the city centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham is a snowy city relative to other large UK conurbations, due to its inland location and comparatively high elevation.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Between 1961 and 1990 Birmingham Airport averaged 13.0 days of snow lying annually, compared to 5.33 at London Heathrow.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Snow showers often pass through the city via the Cheshire gap on north westerly airstreams, but can also come off the North Sea from north easterly airstreams.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city has been known to experience tornadoes: according to TORRO, Birmingham experienced 15 significant tornadoes between 1946 and 2005, with some being incredibly destructive.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Most notably, a deadly F3 tornado on June 14, 1931, and another IF3 tornado which followed a similar path on 28 July 2005, becoming the United Kingdom's costliest tornado on record.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] On 23 November 1981, during a record-breaking nationwide tornado outbreak, three tornadoes touched down within the Birmingham city limits – in Erdington, Selly Oak, and King's Heath–with three more tornadoes touching down within the boundaries of the wider West Midlands county.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Notable tornadoes also struck the city in 1946, 1968, and 1999.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] There are 571 parks within Birmingham – more than any other European city – totalling over 3,500 hectares (14 sq mi) of public open space.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city has over six million trees, and 250 miles (400 kilometres) of urban brooks and streams.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Sutton Park, which covers 2,400 acres (971 ha) in the north of the city, is the largest urban park in Europe and a national nature reserve.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham Botanical Gardens, located close to the city centre, retains the regency landscape of its original design by J.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Loudon in 1829, while the Winterbourne Botanic Garden in Edgbaston reflects the more informal Arts and Crafts tastes of its Edwardian origins.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Several green spaces within the borough are designated as green belt, as a portion of the wider West Midlands Green Belt.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This is a strategic local government policy used to prevent urban sprawl and preserve greenfield land.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The 2021 census recorded 1,144,900 people living in Birmingham, an increase of about 6.7% from 2011 when 1,073,045 were recorded.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] It is the 27th largest city in Europe by population within its city boundary.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham's continuous urban area extends beyond the city's boundaries: the Birmingham Larger Urban Zone, a Eurostat measure of the functional city-region approximated to local government districts, had a population of 2,357,100 in 2004.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In addition to Birmingham itself, the LUZ (West Midlands conurbation) includes the Metropolitan Boroughs of Dudley, Sandwell, Solihull and Walsall, along with the districts of Lichfield, Tamworth, North Warwickshire and Bromsgrove.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Beyond this is the wider metropolitan area with a population numbering 3,558,916 in 2019 according to Eurostat.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] About 305,688 or 26.7% of the population in 2021 were foreign-born, making it a city with one of the largest migrant populations in Europe.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The 2021 census showed 26.7% of the population were born outside the UK, an increase of 4.5% percentage points from 2011.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Figures showed that the five largest foreign-born groups living in Birmingham were born in Pakistan, India, Bangladesh, Romania and Jamaica.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 2011, 57% of primary and 52% of secondary pupils were from non-White British families.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] As of 2021, 31.6% of school pupils in Birmingham were White, 37.7% were Asian, 12.6% were Black, 9.7% were Mixed race and 8.4% were Other.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] There is particularly a large community of Asian descent, especially from Pakistani, Indian and Bangladeshi backgrounds, as well as Afro-Caribbeans from the Commonwealth, and a solid Chinese presence through migrants from the former colony of Hong Kong.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham also has an older Irish connection, with the city having the largest population of Irish in mainland Britain and home to its only Irish quarter, Digbeth.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In Birmingham, 65.9% of the population were aged between 15 and 64, higher than when compared to the national average of 64.1% in England and Wales.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Furthermore, 20.9% of the population were aged under 15, higher than the national average of 17.4% while the population aged over 65 was 13.1%, which was lower than the national average of 18.6% respectively.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham is one of the youngest cities in Europe with 40% of its population below the age of 25 and the median age being 34 years of age, below the national average of 40.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Christianity is the largest religion within Birmingham, with 34% of residents identifying as Christians in the 2021 census.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city's religious profile is highly diverse: outside London, Birmingham has the United Kingdom's largest Muslim, Sikh and Buddhist communities; its second largest Hindu community; and its seventh largest Jewish community.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Between the 2001, 2011, and 2021 censuses, the proportion of Christians in Birmingham decreased from 59.1% to 46.1% to 34%, while the proportion of Muslims increased from 14.3% to 21.8% to 29.9% and the proportion of people with no religious affiliation increased from 12.4% to 19.3% to 24.1%.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] All other religions remained proportionately similar.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] St Philip's Cathedral was upgraded from church status when the Anglican Diocese of Birmingham was created in 1905.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] There are two other cathedrals: St Chad's, seat of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Birmingham and the Greek Orthodox Cathedral of the Dormition of the Mother of God and St Andrew.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The Coptic Orthodox Diocese of the Midlands is also based at Birmingham, with a cathedral under construction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The original parish church of Birmingham, St Martin in the Bull Ring, is Grade II* listed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] A short distance from Five Ways the Birmingham Oratory was completed in 1910 on the site of Cardinal Newman's original foundation.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] There are several Christadelphian meeting halls in the city and the Christadelphian Magazine and Publishing Group has its headquarters in Hall Green.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The oldest surviving synagogue in Birmingham is the 1825 Greek Revival Severn Street Synagogue, now a Freemasons' Lodge hall.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] It was replaced in 1856 by the Grade II* listed Singers Hill Synagogue.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham Central Mosque, one of the largest in Europe, was constructed in the 1960s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] During the late 1990s Ghamkol Shariff Masjid was built in Small Heath.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The Guru Nanak Nishkam Sewak Jatha Sikh Gurdwara was built on Soho Road in Handsworth in the late 1970s and the Theravada Buddhist Dhamma Talaka Peace Pagoda near Edgbaston Reservoir in the 1990s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Winners' Chapel also maintains physical presence in Digbeth.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham grew to prominence as a centre of manufacturing and engineering.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The economy of Birmingham is dominated by the service sector, which accounted for 88% of the city's employment in 2012.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham is the largest centre in the UK for employment in public administration, education and health; and after Leeds the second-largest centre outside London for employment in financial and other business services.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The Gun Quarter is a district of the city that was, for many years, a centre of the world's gun-manufacturing industry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The first recorded gun maker in Birmingham was in 1630, and locally made muskets were used in the English Civil War.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The Gun Quarter is an industrial area to the north of the city centre, bounded by Steelhouse Lane, Shadwell Street, and Loveday Street, specialising in the production of military firearms and sporting guns.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Many buildings in the area are disused but plans are in place for redevelopment including in Shadwell Street and Vesey Street.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The wider metropolitan economy is the second-largest in the United Kingdom with a GDP of $121.1 billion (2014 estimate, PPP).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] With major facilities such as the National Exhibition Centre and International Convention Centre, Birmingham attracts 42% of the UK's total conference and exhibition trade.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In 2012, manufacturing accounted for 8% of the employment in Birmingham, a figure below the average for the UK as a whole.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Major industrial plants in the city include Jaguar Land Rover in Castle Bromwich and Cadbury in Bournville, with large local producers also supporting a supply chain of precision-based small manufacturers and craft industries.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] More traditional industries also remain: 40% of the jewellery made in the UK is still produced by the 300 independent manufacturers of the city's Jewellery Quarter, continuing a trade first recorded in Birmingham in 1308.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In June 2025, Birmingham was declared a World Craft City by the World Crafts Council, because of its continuing jewellery trade.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham's GVA was estimated to be £24.8 billion in 2015, economic growth accelerated each successive year between 2013 and 2015, and with an annual growth of 4.2% in 2015, GVA per head grew at the second-fastest rate of England's eight "Core Cities".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The value of manufacturing output in the city declined by 21% in real terms between 1997 and 2010, but the value of financial and insurance activities more than doubled.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] With 16,281 start-ups registered during 2013, Birmingham has the highest level of entrepreneurial activity outside London, while the number of registered businesses in the city grew by 8.1% during 2016.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Birmingham was behind only London and Edinburgh for private sector job creation between 2010 and 2013.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Economic inequality in Birmingham is greater than in any other major English city, exceeded only by Glasgow in the United Kingdom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Levels of unemployment are among the highest in the country, with 10% of the economically active population unemployed in June 2016.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] In the inner-city wards of Aston and Washwood Heath, the figure is higher than 30%.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Two-fifths of Birmingham's population live in areas classified as in the 10% most deprived parts of England, and overall Birmingham is the most deprived local authority in England in terms of income and employment deprivation.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city's infant mortality rate is high, around 60% worse than the national average.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] Meanwhile, just 49% of women have jobs, compared to 65% nationally, and only 28% of the working-age population in Birmingham have degree level qualifications in contrast to the average of 34% across other core cities.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] According to the 2014 Mercer Quality of Living Survey, Birmingham was placed 51st in the world, which was the second-highest rating in the UK.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The city's quality of life rating has continued to improve over the years and Birmingham was ranked 49th in the world in the 2019 survey.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This is the first time it has featured in the top 50.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] The Big City Plan of 2008 aims to move the city into the index's top 20 by 2026.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] An area of the city has been designated an enterprise zone, with tax relief and simplified planning to lure investment.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] According to 2019 property investment research, Birmingham is rated as the number one location for "the best places to invest in property in the UK".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p01] This was attributed to a 5% increase in house prices and local investment into infrastructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has two major public art collections.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham Museum & Art Gallery is best known for its works by the Pre-Raphaelites, a collection "of outstanding importance".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It also holds a significant selection of old masters – including major works by Bellini, Rubens, Canaletto and Claude – and particularly strong collections of 17th-century Italian Baroque painting and English watercolours.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Its design holdings include Europe's pre-eminent collections of ceramics and fine metalwork.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Barber Institute of Fine Arts in Edgbaston is one of the finest small art galleries in the world, with a collection of exceptional quality representing Western art from the 13th century to the present day.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham Museums Trust runs other museums in the city including Aston Hall, Blakesley Hall, the Museum of the Jewellery Quarter, Soho House and Sarehole Mill.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Back to Backs are the last surviving court of back-to-back houses in the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Cadbury World is a museum showing visitors the stages and steps of chocolate production and the history of chocolate and the company.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Ikon Gallery hosts displays of contemporary art, as does Eastside Projects.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Thinktank is Birmingham's main science museum, with a giant screen cinema, a planetarium and a collection that includes the *Smethwick Engine*, the world's oldest working steam engine.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other science-based museums include the National Sea Life Centre in Brindleyplace, the Lapworth Museum of Geology at the University of Birmingham and the Centre of the Earth environmental education centre in Winson Green.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra's home venue is Symphony Hall.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other notable professional orchestras based in the city include the Birmingham Contemporary Music Group, the Royal Ballet Sinfonia and Ex Cathedra, a Baroque chamber choir and period instrument orchestra.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Orchestra of the Swan is the resident chamber orchestra at Birmingham Town Hall, where weekly recitals have also been given by the City Organist since 1834.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Triennial Music Festivals took place from 1784 to 1912.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Music was specially composed, conducted or performed by Mendelssohn, Gounod, Sullivan, Dvořák, Bantock and Edward Elgar, who wrote four of his most famous choral pieces for Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Elgar's *The Dream of Gerontius* had its début performance there in 1900.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Composers born in the city include Albert William Ketèlbey and Andrew Glover.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Jazz has been popular in the city since the 1920s, and there are many regular festivals such as the Harmonic Festival, the Mostly Jazz Festival and the annual International Jazz Festival.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] During the 1960s, Birmingham was the home of a music scene comparable to that of Liverpool.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It was "a seething cauldron of musical activity", and the international success of groups such as The Move, The Spencer Davis Group, The Moody Blues, Traffic and the Electric Light Orchestra had a collective influence that stretched into the 1970s and beyond.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city was a centre for early heavy metal music, with pioneering metal bands from the late 1960s and 1970s such as Black Sabbath, Judas Priest, and half of Led Zeppelin having come from Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The next decade saw the metal bands Napalm Death and Godflesh emerge from the city, as well as Benediction and the extreme black death metal act Anaal Nathrakh later.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The funeral doom band Esoteric has been operating in the sub-genre since 1992.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham was the birthplace of modern bhangra in the 1960s, and by the 1980s had established itself as the global centre of bhangra culture, which has grown into a global phenomenon embraced by members of the Indian diaspora worldwide from Los Angeles to Singapore.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The 1970s also saw the rise of reggae and ska in the city with such bands as Steel Pulse, UB40, Musical Youth, The Beat and Beshara, expounding racial unity with politically leftist lyrics and multiracial line-ups, mirroring social currents in Birmingham at that time.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other popular bands from Birmingham include Duran Duran, Johnny Foreigner, Fine Young Cannibals, Felt, Broadcast, Ocean Colour Scene, The Streets, The Twang, King Adora, Dexys Midnight Runners, and Magnum.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Musicians Jeff Lynne, Ozzy Osbourne, Tony Iommi, Bill Ward, Geezer Butler, GBH, John Lodge, Roy Wood, Joan Armatrading, Toyah Willcox, Denny Laine, Sukshinder Shinda, Apache Indian, Steve Winwood, Jamelia, Oceans Ate Alaska, Fyfe Dangerfield and Laura Mvula all grew up in the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham Repertory Theatre is Britain's longest-established producing theatre, presenting a wide variety of work in its three auditoria on Centenary Square and touring nationally and internationally.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other producing theatres in the city include the Blue Orange Theatre in the Jewellery Quarter; the Old Rep, home stage of the Birmingham Stage Company; and @ A.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Harris, the base of the experimental Stan's Cafe theatre company, located within a working metal fabricators' factory.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Touring theatre companies include the politically radical Banner Theatre, the Maverick Theatre Company and Kindle Theatre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Royal Ballet is one of the United Kingdom's five major ballet companies and one of three based outside London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is resident at the Birmingham Hippodrome and tours extensively nationally and internationally.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The company's associated ballet school – Elmhurst School for Dance in Edgbaston – is the oldest vocational dance school in the country.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Opera Company under artistic director Graham Vick has developed an international reputation for its avant-garde productions, which often take place in factories, abandoned buildings and other found spaces around the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] More conventional seasons by Welsh National Opera and other visiting opera companies take place regularly at the Birmingham Hippodrome.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The first dedicated comedy club outside London, The Glee Club, was opened in The Arcadian Centre, city centre, in 1994, and continues to host performances by leading regional, national and international acts.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In the 1920s, Oscar Deutsch opened his first Odeon cinema in the UK, in Perry Barr.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] By 1930, the Odeon brand was a household name and still thrives today.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Electric on Station Street opened on 27 December 1909, and is the oldest independent working cinema in the UK, continuing to operate despite multiple threats of closure over the years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In 1931, the Birmingham Film Society was established, with an inaugural screening on 18 January 1931 at the Hampton Cinema in Livery Street.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The largest cinema screen in the West Midlands was located at Millennium Point in Birmingham's Eastside, and opened in September 2001 as an IMAX format screen.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Unable to maintain commercial viability as large 3D screens became commonplace across commercial cinema multiplexes, the IMAX screen was closed and downgraded in September 2011, before its replacement Giant Screen Cinema was closed in January 2015.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city's primary film festival, the Birmingham Film Festival, was co-founded by filmmaker Kevin McDonagh and actor Dean Williams in 2015 and has been held every year since.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It patrons include *Peaky Blinders* creator Steven Knight and advertising executive Trevor Beattie, whilst its Grand Jury has featured judges including actress Kia Pegg and filmmakers Michael B.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Screen West Midlands, the regional screen agency for the West Midlands, is based in the city's Jewellery Quarter.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Film Birmingham is the Birmingham City Council's Film and Television office, handling queries and filming requests from national and international productions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Literary figures associated with Birmingham include Samuel Johnson who stayed in Birmingham for a short period and was born in nearby Lichfield.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Arthur Conan Doyle worked in the Aston area of Birmingham whilst poet Louis MacNeice lived in Birmingham for six years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It was whilst staying in Birmingham that American author Washington Irving produced several of his most famous literary works, such as *Bracebridge Hall* and *The Humorists, A Medley* which are based on Aston Hall, as well as *The Legend of Sleepy Hollow* and *Rip Van Winkle*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Auden grew up in the Harborne area of the city and during the 1930s formed the core of the Auden Group with Birmingham University lecturer Louis MacNeice.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other influential poets associated with Birmingham include Roi Kwabena, who was the city's sixth poet laureate, and Benjamin Zephaniah, who was born in the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Tolkien was brought up in the Kings Heath area of Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] He referred to Birmingham as his home town and to himself as a ‘Birmingham man’.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There is a dedicated 'Tolkien Trail' across Birmingham which takes those who follow it to the landmarks which are said to have inspired Tolkien's works.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The political playwright David Edgar was born in Birmingham, and the science fiction author John Wyndham spent his early childhood in the Edgbaston area of the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has a vibrant contemporary literary scene, with local authors including David Lodge, Jim Crace, Jonathan Coe, Joel Lane and Judith Cutler.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city's leading contemporary literary publisher is the Tindal Street Press, whose authors include prize-winning novelists Catherine O'Flynn, Clare Morrall and Austin Clarke.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham School of landscape artists emerged with Daniel Bond in the 1760s and was to last into the mid-19th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Its most important figure was David Cox, whose later works make him an important precursor of impressionism.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The influence of the Royal Birmingham Society of Artists and the Birmingham School of Art made Birmingham an important centre of Victorian art, particularly within the Pre-Raphaelite and Arts and Crafts movements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Major figures included the Pre-Raphaelite and symbolist Edward Burne-Jones; Walter Langley, the first of the Newlyn School painters; and Joseph Southall, leader of the group of artists and craftsmen known as the Birmingham Group.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Surrealists were among the "harbingers of surrealism" in Britain in the 1930s and the movement's most active members in the 1940s, while more abstract artists associated with the city included Lee Bank-born David Bomberg and CoBrA member William Gear.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham's role as a manufacturing and printing centre has supported strong local traditions of graphic design and product design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Iconic works by Birmingham designers include the Baskerville font, Ruskin Pottery, the Acme Thunderer whistle, the Art Deco branding of the Odeon Cinemas and the Mini.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Nightlife in Birmingham is mainly concentrated along Broad Street and into Brindleyplace.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Although in more recent years, Broad Street has lost its popularity due to the closing of several clubs; the Arcadian now has more popularity in terms of nightlife.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Outside the Broad Street area are many stylish and underground venues.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Medicine Bar in the Custard Factory, hmv Institute, Rainbow Pub and Air are large clubs and bars in Digbeth.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Around Birmingham Chinatown are areas such as the Arcadian and Hurst Street Gay Village, that abound with bars and clubs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Summer Row, The Mailbox, O2 Academy in Bristol Street, Snobs Nightclub, St Philips/Colmore Row, St Paul's Square and the Jewellery Quarter all have a vibrant night life.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There are a number of late night pubs in the Irish Quarter.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Outside the city centre is Star City entertainment complex on the former site of Nechells Power Station.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is home to many national, religious, and cultural festivals, including a St.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city's largest single-day event is its St.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Patrick's Day parade (Europe's second largest, after Dublin).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Nowka Bais is a Bengali boat racing festival which takes place annually in Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is a leading cultural event in the West Midlands attracting not only the Bangladeshi diaspora but a variety of cultures.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is also the largest kind of boat race in the United Kingdom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other multicultural events include the Bangla Mela and the Vaisakhi Mela.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Heritage Festival is a Mardi Gras style event in August.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Caribbean and African culture are celebrated with parades and street performances by buskers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Caribbean-style Birmingham International Carnival takes place in odd-numbered years.From 1997 until December 2006, the city hosted an annual arts festival, ArtsFest, the largest free arts festival in the UK at the time.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The UK's largest two-day Gay Pride is Birmingham Pride (LGBT festival), which is typically held over the spring bank holiday weekend in May.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The streets of Birmingham's gay district pulsate with a carnival parade, live music, a dance arena with DJs, cabaret stage, women's arena and a community village.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In addition, founded and organised by local comedian Joe Lycett with support from local businesses and the community, the smaller Queens Heath Pride is held annually, typically late June to early July.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] With stalls, events, and free entry, Queens Heath Pride lasts one day and takes place on York Road and Heathfield Road, Kings Heath.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The event doesn't charge for entry, but independent market stalls sell a range of souvenirs, clothes, food, and drinks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Tattoo is a long-standing military show held annually at the National Indoor Arena.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Comedy Festival (since 2001; 10 days in October), has been headlined by such acts as Peter Kay, The Fast Show, Jimmy Carr, Lee Evans and Lenny Henry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Since 2001, Birmingham has been host to the Frankfurt Christmas Market.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Modelled on its German counterpart, it has grown to become the UK's largest outdoor Christmas market and is the largest German market outside Germany and Austria, attracting over 3.1 million visitors in 2010 and over 5 million visitors in 2011.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The biennial Birmingham International Dance Festival (BIDF) started in 2008, organised by DanceXchange and involving indoor and outdoor venues across the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other festivals in the city include the Birmingham International Jazz Festival.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Moseley Folk and Arts Festival, and Mostly Jazz Festival.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham's development as a commercial town was originally based around its market for agricultural produce, established by royal charter in 1166.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is the only city outside London to have five Michelin-starred restaurants: Simpson's in Edgbaston, Carters of Moseley, and Purnell's, Opheem, and Adam's in the city centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham based breweries included Ansells, Davenport's and Mitchells & Butlers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Aston Manor Brewery is currently the only brewery of any significant size.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Many fine Victorian pubs and bars can still be found across the city, whilst there is also a plethora of more modern nightclubs and bars, notably along Broad Street.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Wing Yip food empire first began in the city and now has its headquarters in Nechells.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Balti, a type of curry, was invented in the city, which has received much acclaim for the 'Balti Belt' or 'Balti Triangle'.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Famous food brands that originated in Birmingham include Typhoo tea, Bird's Custard, Cadbury's chocolate and HP Sauce.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There is also a thriving independent and artisan food sector in Birmingham, encompassing microbreweries like Two Towers, and collective bakeries such as Loaf.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Recent years have seen these businesses increasingly showcased at farmers markets, popular street food events and food festivals including Birmingham Independent Food Fair.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is home to many entertainment and leisure venues, including Europe's largest leisure and entertainment complex Star City as well as Europe's first out-of-city-centre entertainment and leisure complex Resorts World Birmingham owned by the Genting Group.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Mailbox which caters for more affluent clients is based within the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is chiefly a product of the 18th, 19th and 20th centuries; its growth began during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Consequently, relatively few buildings survive from its earlier history and those that do are protected.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There are 1,946 listed buildings in Birmingham and thirteen scheduled monuments.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham City Council also operate a locally listing scheme for buildings that do not fully meet the criteria for statutorily listed status.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Traces of medieval Birmingham can be seen in the oldest churches, notably the original parish church, St Martin in the Bull Ring.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] A few other buildings from the medieval and Tudor periods survive, among them the *Lad in the Lane* and *The Old Crown*, the 15th century *Saracen's Head* public house and Old Grammar School in Kings Norton and Blakesley Hall.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] A number of Georgian buildings survive, including St Philip's Cathedral, Soho House, Perrott's Folly, the Town Hall and much of St Paul's Square.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Victorian era saw extensive building across the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Major civic buildings such as the Victoria Law Courts (in characteristic red brick and terracotta), the Council House and the Museum & Art Gallery were constructed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] St Chad's Cathedral was the first Roman Catholic cathedral to be built in the UK since the Reformation.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Across the city, the need to house the industrial workers gave rise to miles of redbrick streets and terraces, many of back-to-back houses, some of which were later to become inner-city slums.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Postwar redevelopment and anti-Victorianism resulted in the loss of dozens of Victorian buildings like New Street station and the old Central Library, often replaced by brutalist architecture.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Sir Herbert Manzoni, City Engineer and Surveyor of Birmingham from 1935 until 1963, believed conservation of old buildings was sentimental and that the city did not have any of worth anyway.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In inner-city areas too, much Victorian housing was demolished and redeveloped.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Existing communities were relocated to tower block estates like Castle Vale.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In a partial reaction against the Manzoni years, Birmingham City Council is demolishing some of the brutalist buildings like the Central Library and has an extensive tower block demolition and renovation programme.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Funding for many of these projects has come from the European Union; the Town Hall for example received £3 million in funding from the European Regional Development Fund.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Highrise development has slowed since the 1970s and mainly in recent years because of enforcements imposed by the Civil Aviation Authority on the heights of buildings as they could affect aircraft from the Airport (e.g.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] People from Birmingham are called Brummies, a term derived from the city's nickname of "Brum", which originates from the city's old name, Brummagem.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Brummie accent and dialect are particularly distinctive.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Partly due to its central location, Birmingham is a major transport hub for motorway, railway and canal networks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city is served by the M5, M6, M40 and M42 motorways, and possibly the most well known motorway junction in the United Kingdom: Spaghetti Junction, a colloquial name for the Gravelly Hill Interchange.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The M6 passes through the city on the Bromford Viaduct, which at 3.5 miles (5.6 km) is the longest bridge in the UK.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Middleway (A4540) is a ring road that runs around the city centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In the past there used to be a smaller ring road in the core of the city named Inner Ring Road.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham introduced a Clean Air Zone from 1 June 2021, which charges polluting vehicles to travel into the city centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham Airport, located 6 miles (9.7 km) east of the city centre in the neighbouring borough of Solihull, is the seventh busiest airport by passenger traffic in the UK and the third busiest outside the London area, after Manchester and Edinburgh.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is a major base for easyJet, Jet2, Ryanair and TUI Airways, and is the former headquarters and main hub of now-defunct airline, Fly:Be.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Airline services operate from Birmingham to many destinations in Europe, Africa, the Americas, Middle East, Asia and Oceania.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] is one of largest railway stations in the UK and the busiest outside London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham's local public transport network is co-ordinated by Transport for West Midlands (TfWM) which is a branch of the West Midlands Combined Authority.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has a high level of public transport usage; in 2023, 59% of morning peak trips into Birmingham were made by public transport, while 36% of journeys were made by private car.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Bus was the most popular public transport mode, accounting for 29.5% of journeys, followed by rail at 26.9% and the Metro at 2.6%.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There is currently no underground system in Birmingham; it is the largest city in Europe not to have one.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In recent years, ideas of an underground system have started to appear, but none so far have been planned in earnest primarily due to the ongoing expansion of the West Midlands Metro tram network being viewed as a higher priority.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The main railway station in the city is Birmingham New Street, which is the busiest railway station in the UK outside London, both for passenger entries/exits and for passenger interchanges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is the national hub for CrossCountry, the most extensive long-distance train network in Britain, and a major destination for Avanti West Coast services from London Euston, Glasgow Central and Edinburgh Waverley.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham Moor Street and Birmingham Snow Hill are the northern termini for Chiltern Railways trains running from London Marylebone and Oxford.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Snow Hill, north on the same line, is another main station serving Birmingham's Colmore Business district, for other services towards Kidderminster and Worcester.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Both stations serve West Midlands Railway and Chiltern Railway services to Kidderminster, Worcester Foregate Street, Leamington Spa, Stratford-upon-Avon, and Dorridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Curzon Street railway station, currently under construction, adjacent to Moor Street, will be the terminus for trains to the city on High Speed 2, the first phase of which has, as of June 2025, been delayed to beyond 2033, with no new date given.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham and the surrounding region have a network of local and suburban railways, mostly operated by West Midlands Trains.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There are a total of 75 railway stations within the West Midlands county, 37 of which are within Birmingham's city boundaries.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Suburban railway lines in Birmingham include the Cross-City Line, the Chase Line, the Snow Hill Lines, the Birmingham loop and the recently re-opened Camp Hill Line.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In 2024/2025, there were nearly 66 million rail passenger journeys within the TfWM area, a significant increase over the 23 million back in 2000/01.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Historically, Birmingham had a substantial tram system operated by Birmingham Corporation Tramways which was closed in 1953.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In 1999, trams returned to the city with the West Midlands Metro (formerly known as *Midland Metro*) which operates services to the city of Wolverhampton.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Bus networks throughout the city and wider region are widespread.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] 247 million bus journeys were made in the TfWM area in 2024/25.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Bus routes are mainly operated commercially by private companies, although TfWM and local councils subsidise socially necessary services.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The number 11 Outer Circle bus route, run by National Express West Midlands, which operates in both clockwise and anti-clockwise directions around the outskirts of the city, is the longest urban bus route in Europe, being over 26 miles (42 km) long with 272 bus stops.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The headquarters of Mobico Group are located in Digbeth, who own both National Express West Midlands and National Express Coaches, are based in offices above Birmingham Coach Station which also forms the latter's national hub.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] As well as National Express Coaches, the city is also served by Flixbus.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Sustrans' National Cycle Route 5 goes through central Birmingham, connecting with National Cycle Route 81 at Smethwick.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] National Cycle Route 535 from Sutton Coldfield terminates just north of Birmingham Snow Hill railway station.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In 2021, Transport for West Midlands launched a cycle hire scheme involving over 300 bikes and 43 docking stations across the West Midlands, including central Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] An extensive canal system still remains in Birmingham from the Industrial Revolution.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city has more miles of canal than Venice, though the canals in Birmingham are a less prominent and essential feature due to the larger size of the city and the fact that few of its buildings are accessed by canal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The canals are mainly used today for leisure purposes; canal side regeneration schemes such as Brindleyplace have turned the canals into a tourist attraction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is home to five universities: Aston University, University of Birmingham, Birmingham City University, University College Birmingham and Newman University.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city also hosts major campuses of the University of Law and BPP University, as well as the Open University's West Midlands regional base.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] In 2011 Birmingham had 78,259 full-time students from all over the world aged 18–74 resident in the city during term time, more than any other city in the United Kingdom outside London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has 32,690 research students, also the highest number of any major city outside London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Business School, established by Sir William Ashley in 1902, is the oldest graduate-level business school in the United Kingdom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Another top business school in the city includes Aston Business School, one of fewer than 1% of business schools globally to be granted triple accreditation, and Birmingham City Business School.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Royal Birmingham Conservatoire, part of Birmingham City University, offers professional training in music and acting.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is an important centre for religious education.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham Metropolitan College is one of the largest further education colleges in the country, with fourteen campuses spread across Birmingham and into the Black Country and Worcestershire.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] South & City College Birmingham has nine campuses spread throughout the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Bournville College is based in a £66 million, 4.2 acre campus in Longbridge that opened in 2011.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Fircroft College is a residential college based in a former Edwardian mansion in Selly Oak, founded in 1909 around a strong commitment to social justice, with many courses aimed at students with few prior formal qualifications.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Queen Alexandra College is a specialist college based in Harborne offering further education to visually impaired or disabled students from all over the United Kingdom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham City Council is England's largest local education authority, directly or indirectly responsible for nursery schools, primary schools, secondary schools, special schools, sixth form colleges, further education colleges, and adult education.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It provides around 3,500 adult education courses throughout the year.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Most of Birmingham's state schools are academy schools, community schools, free schools and voluntary aided schools.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Since the 1970s, most secondary schools in Birmingham have been 11-–-16/18 comprehensive schools, while post GCSE students have the choice of continuing their education in either a school's sixth form or at a further education college.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] King Edward's School, Birmingham, founded in 1552 by King Edward VI, is one of the oldest schools in the city, teaching GCSE and IB, with alumni including J R R Tolkien, author of the *Lord of the Rings* books and *The Hobbit*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Independent schools in the city include the Birmingham Blue Coat School, King Edward VI High School for Girls and Edgbaston High School for Girls.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Bishop Vesey's Grammar School was founded by Bishop Vesey in 1527.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The former Birmingham Central Library, opened in 1972, was considered to be the largest municipal library in Europe.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Six of its collections were designated by the Arts Council England as being "pre-eminent collections of national and international importance", out of only eight collections to be so recognised in local authority libraries nationwide.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] A new Library of Birmingham in Centenary Square, replacing Central Library, was opened on 3 September 2013.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It was designed by the Dutch architects Mecanoo and has been described as "a kind of public forum ... a memorial, a shrine, to the book and to literature".
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The library is viewed by the Birmingham City Council as a flagship project for the city's redevelopment.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It has been described as the largest public library in the United Kingdom, the largest public cultural space in Europe, and the largest regional library in Europe.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] 2,414,860 visitors came to the library in 2014 making it the 10th most popular visitor attraction in the UK.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There are 41 local libraries in Birmingham, plus a regular mobile library service.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The library service has 4 million visitors annually.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Law enforcement in Birmingham is carried out by West Midlands Police, whose headquarters are at Lloyd House in the city centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] With 87.92 recorded offences per 1000 population in 2009–10, Birmingham's crime rate is above the average for England and Wales, but lower than any of England's other major core cities and lower than many smaller cities such as Oxford, Cambridge or Brighton.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Fire and rescue services in Birmingham are provided by West Midlands Fire Service and emergency medical care by West Midlands Ambulance Service.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There are several major National Health Service hospitals in Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Queen Elizabeth Hospital, adjacent to the Birmingham Medical School in Edgbaston, is one of the largest teaching hospitals in the United Kingdom with over 1,200 beds.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is a major trauma centre offering services to the extended West Midlands region and houses the largest single-floor critical care unit in the world, with 100 beds.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The hospital has the largest solid organ transplantation programme in Europe as well as the largest renal transplant programme in the United Kingdom and it is a national specialist centre for liver, heart and lung transplantation, as well as cancer studies.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is the home of the Royal Centre for Defence Medicine for military personnel injured in conflict zones.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Other general hospitals in the city include Heartlands Hospital in Bordesley Green, Good Hope Hospital in Sutton Coldfield and City Hospital in Winson Green.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] There are also many specialist hospitals, such as Birmingham Children's Hospital, Birmingham Women's Hospital, Birmingham Dental Hospital, and the Royal Orthopaedic Hospital.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham saw the first ever use of radiography in an operation, and the UK's first ever hole-in-the-heart operation was performed at Birmingham Children's Hospital.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Corporation Water Department was set up in 1876 to supply water to Birmingham, up until 1974 when its responsibilities were transferred to Severn Trent Water.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Most of Birmingham's water is supplied by the Elan aqueduct, opened in 1904; water is fed by gravity to Frankley Reservoir, Frankley, and Bartley Reservoir, Bartley Green, from reservoirs in the Elan Valley, Wales.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Within Birmingham the Tyseley Energy from Waste Plant, a large incineration plant built in 1996 for Veolia, burns some 366,414 tonnes of household waste annually and produces 166,230 MWh of electricity for the National Grid along with 282,013 tonnes of carbon dioxide.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has played an important part in the history of modern sport.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The modern game of tennis was developed between 1859 and 1865 by Harry Gem and his friend Augurio Perera at Perera's house in Edgbaston, with the Edgbaston Archery and Lawn Tennis Society remaining the oldest tennis club in the world.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham and District Cricket League is the oldest cricket league in the world, and Birmingham was the host for the first ever Cricket World Cup, a Women's Cricket World Cup in 1973.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham was the first city to be named National City of Sport by the Sports Council.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham was selected ahead of London and Manchester to bid for the 1992 Summer Olympics, but was unsuccessful in the final selection process, which was won by Barcelona.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Today, the city is home of two of the country's oldest professional football teams: Aston Villa F.C., which was founded in 1874 and plays at Villa Park; and Birmingham City F.C., which was founded in 1875 and plays at St Andrew's.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Rivalry between the clubs is fierce and the fixture between the two is called the Second City derby.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Aston Villa currently play in the Premier League while Birmingham City currently play in the EFL Championship.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] West Bromwich Albion also draw support within the Birmingham area, being located at The Hawthorns just outside the city boundaries in Sandwell.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Rival football team Coventry City also played briefly at St Andrew's for two seasons between 2019 and 2021 due to an ongoing dispute with their landlords over use of the Coventry Building Society Arena.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Warwickshire County Cricket Club play at Edgbaston Cricket Ground, which also hosts test cricket and one day internationals and is the largest cricket ground in the United Kingdom after Lord's.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Edgbaston was the scene of the highest ever score by a batsman in first-class cricket, when Brian Lara scored 501 not out for Warwickshire in 1994.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is also home to professional Rugby Union clubs such as Birmingham Moseley and Birmingham & Solihull.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city also has a semiprofessional Rugby League club, the Midlands Hurricanes as well as an amateur club the Birmingham Bulldogs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city is also home to one of the oldest American football teams in the BAFA National Leagues, the Birmingham Bulls and a baseball club, Birmingham Baseball Club, with two teams, the Metalheads and the Bats.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Two major championship golf courses lie on the city's outskirts.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Belfry near Sutton Coldfield is the headquarters of the Professional Golfers' Association and has hosted the Ryder Cup more times than any other venue.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Forest of Arden Hotel and Country Club near Birmingham Airport is also a regular host of tournaments on the PGA European Tour, including the British Masters and the English Open.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Birmingham Classic is, alongside Wimbledon and Eastbourne, one of only three UK tennis tournaments on the WTA Tour.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is played annually at the Edgbaston Priory Club, which in 2010 announced plans for a multimillion-pound redevelopment, including a new showcase centre court and a museum celebrating the game's Birmingham origins.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Alexander Stadium in Perry Barr is the headquarters of UK Athletics, and one of only two British venues to host fixtures in the elite international IAAF Diamond League.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] It is also the home of Birchfield Harriers, which has many international athletes among its members.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Professional boxing, hockey, skateboarding, stock-car racing, greyhound racing and speedway also take place within the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Since 1994 Birmingham has hosted the All England Open Badminton Championships at Arena Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham hosted the 2022 Commonwealth Games, which took place between 28 July and 8 August 2022.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] This was the first time that Birmingham hosted the Commonwealth Games and the 22nd edition of the Commonwealth Games to take place.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Alexander Stadium, which hosted the opening and closing ceremonies and athletics was renovated, and the capacity was increased to 30,000 seats.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The event contributed £1.2 billion to the economy of the United Kingdom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is home to a media industry that includes news and magazine publishers, radio and television networks, film production and specialist educational media training.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has several major local newspapers – the daily *Birmingham Mail* and the weekly *Birmingham Post* and *Sunday Mercury*, all owned by Reach plc.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] *Forward* is a freesheet produced by Birmingham City Council, which is distributed to homes in the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is also the hub for various national ethnic media, lifestyle magazines, digital news platforms, and the base for two regional Metro editions (East and West Midlands).
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has three mainstream digital-only news publishers, *I Am Birmingham*, *Birmingham Updates* and *Second City*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham has a long cinematic history; The Electric on Station Street was the oldest working cinema in the UK until its closure in 2024.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Birmingham is the location for several British and international film productions including *Felicia's Journey* of 1999, which used locations in Birmingham that were used in *Take Me High* of 1973 to contrast the changes in the city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The Mailbox, in the city centre, is the national headquarters of BBC English Regions and the headquarters of BBC West Midlands and the BBC Birmingham network production centre.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] These were previously located at the Pebble Mill Studios in Edgbaston.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The BBC Drama Village, based in Selly Oak, is a production facility specialising in television drama.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Central/ATV studios in Birmingham was the location for the recording of various programmes for ITV, including *Tiswas* and *Crossroads*, until the complex was closed in 1997, and Central moved to its current Gas Street studios.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Central's output from Birmingham now consists of only the *West* and *East* editions of the regional news programme *ITV News Central*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city is served by numerous national and regional radio stations, as well as hyperlocal radio stations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] These include Hits Radio Birmingham and Greatest Hits Radio Birmingham & The West Midlands, Capital Midlands, Heart West Midlands, and Smooth West Midlands.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The city has a community radio scene, with stations including BRMB, New Style Radio, Brum Radio, Switch Radio, Scratch Radio, Raaj FM, and Unity FM.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] The late night show Late Night Lycett is filmed in Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/birmingham-p02] Guz Khan's comedy-drama series on BBC Three, Man Like Mobeen, is both set and filmed in Small Heath, with small parts in Coventry and Istanbul.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The villages name means 'Brant's farm/settlement'.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The main village of Braunston is situated on a hill above the road and the canals, and formerly had a windmill, the building of which still stands but without any sails.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The village contains several pubs (*The Boathouse*, *The Admiral Nelson*, *The Plough*, and *The Wheatsheaf*), a selection of shops - excellent butchers, hairdressers and village stores incorporating the post office, a fish and chip shop, car servicing garage and a primary school.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The Braunston Manor Hotel has now closed with the main house reverting to residential use and the outhouse buildings redeveloped for a housing development.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] In 1374, the manor itself was the subject of one of a number of property disputes involving the landowning Corbet family.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Braunston's main claims to fame are its canal and church.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] All Saints' Church Braunston has overlooked the village and the villagers for over 10 centuries and the canals and the boat people for over 300 years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Otherwise known as the "Cathedral of the Canals", it has existed since the early 13th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] However, the land on which is stands has been sacred for longer still, as it was used as an ancient tumulus for the local farmsteads as early as the 10th century, although little evidence to this time is available.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Although the original Norman structure was nearly demolished when the site was polluted by several murders in 1290, the church was later rebuilt in the 14th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The second incarnation of the church served the area for over 400 years, until the site was demolished, with authority from Rev.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Alfred Butler Clough in 1848, due to dilapidation of the structure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The third incarnation of the church cost £6,800, money raised primarily through donations and aided by grants from the Church Building Society and the Peterborough Diocesan Society.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Notable contributors to the funds also include Her Majesty the Queen Dowager and the Oxford Canal Company.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] In outline the new church was similar to its mediaeval predecessor in having no north chancel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The body of the church was made wider to provide accommodation for the enlarged population which had followed the coming of the canals.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The new church had the number of seats increased from 363 to 732.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Despite the overwhelming impression of space and light the interior design of the church was rather austere.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The biggest change made was in the appearance of the chancel itself which was transformed by redecoration.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] This was the work of the leading High Church designer, William Butterfield, architect of Rugby School.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Today the church still provides regular services to the area, and often allows visitors to tour the ancient grounds, on non-service days.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The canal alongside Braunston is a junction between the Oxford Canal and the Grand Union Canal, which was once an important part of the national transport system.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Many former boating families have links to Braunston, the churchyard in the village having many graves of boatmen and women.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The village thrived for over 150 years on the canal trade - carrying goods from the Midlands to London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Now it is a centre for leisure activities and boasts by far and away the busiest stretch of canal anywhere in the country.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The unique triangular junction between the two canals has two bridges made at Horseley Ironworks carrying the towpath over the canal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] This was not the original meeting point of the Grand Junction and Oxford Canals: the junction was moved in the course of improvements to the Oxford Canal in the 1830s, prior to which the junction was near where the marina is today, and where a third Horseley Ironworks bridge can be seen.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The canals are no longer used for carrying freight, but are now used mostly by pleasure boats.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Braunston has a marina filled with these pleasure boats and is usually quite busy.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] From the marina, six locks carry the Grand Union Canal up to Braunston Tunnel, some 2,049 yards (1,874 m) long.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Despite its small size, Braunston was once served by two railway stations, both now closed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The first, Braunston London Road was on the former LNWR Weedon to Leamington Spa branch line, via Daventry, was located near the marina and closed in September 1958.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] A couple of miles north-west of Braunston was Braunston and Willoughby station on the former Great Central Main Line, which served Braunston and the village of Willoughby, which it was closer to.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] This was the last main line to be constructed from the north of England to London and opened in March 1899.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Braunston and Willoughby station closed in April 1957 and the line itself in September 1966.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] To the south of the station was the 13-arch Willoughby viaduct crossing the River Leam: the viaduct was demolished about 1980.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Primary School is located in the middle of the village.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] It has one class for each age group from Reception to Year 6, with the capacity for 30 children in each class.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The curriculum is divided up into stages according to age: Foundation Stage – The Reception Class, Key Stage 1 - Years 1 and 2, Key Stage 2 - Years 3, 4, 5 and 6.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Nearby is the small hamlet of Little Braunston.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] Also close to the village are the three lost settlements of Braunston Cleves or Fawcliff, Braunstonbury and Wolfhampcote.
[src:horseley-ironworks/braunston] The village is twinned with Quincy-Voisins in France.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A **bridge** is a structure designed to span an obstacle, such as a river or railway, allowing vehicles, pedestrians, and other loads to pass across.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Most bridges consist of a flat deck, supported by beams, arches, or cables.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] These structures rest on a foundation that is carefully designed to transfer the weight of the bridge to the subsoil without settling.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges can be constructed in a wide variety of forms, determined by the location, intended purpose, and available construction technologies.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Simple bridge structures include beam bridges made from logs, and suspension bridges made of ropes or vines.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Romans and ancient Chinese built major arch bridges of timber, stone, and brick.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] During the Renaissance, advances in science and engineering led to wider bridge spans and more elegant designs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Concrete was perfected in the early 19th century, and arch bridges are now built primarily of concrete or steel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] With the Industrial Revolution came mass-produced steel, which enabled the creation of more complex forms – including truss and cantilever bridges – that permitted bridges to cross wide rivers or deep valleys.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The longest spans use suspension or cable-stayed designs, both of which rely on high-strength steel cables to support the deck.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Over time, the maximum achievable span of bridges has steadily increased, reaching 2 kilometers (1.2 miles) in 2022.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Other bridge forms include multi-span viaducts, which can cross wide valleys; trestles, a common design for carrying heavy trains; and movable bridges including drawbridges and swing bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The design of a bridge must satisfy many requirements, namely connecting to a transportation network, providing adequate clearances, and safely transporting its users.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge must be strong enough to support its own weight as well as the weight of the traffic passing over it.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] It must also tolerate violent, hard-to-predict stresses imposed by the environment, including winds, floods, and earthquakes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] To meet all these goals, bridge engineers typically use limit state design processes and the finite element method.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Many bridges are admired for their beauty, and some spectacular bridges serve as iconic landmarks that provide a sense of pride and identity for the local community.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In art and literature, bridges are frequently used as metaphors to represent connection or transition.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges can create beneficial impacts on a community, including shorter transport times and increased gross domestic product; and also negative effects such as increased pollution and contributions to global warming.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The earliest forms of bridges were simple structures for crossing wetlands and creeks, consisting of wooden boardwalks or logs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Pilings – which are critical elements of bridge construction – were used in Switzerland around 4,000 BC to support stilt houses built over water.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Several corbel arch bridges were built c.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] 13th century BC by the Mycenaean Greece culture, including the Arkadiko Bridge, which is still in existence.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the 7th century BC, Assyrian king Sennacherib constructed stone aqueducts to carry water near the city of Nineveh; one of the aqueducts crossed a small valley at Jerwan with five corbelled arches, and was 280 meters (920 ft) long and 20 meters (66 ft) wide.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In Babylonia in 626 BC, a bridge across the Euphrates was built with an estimated length of 120 to 200 meters (390 to 660 ft).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In India, the *Arthashastra* treatise by Kautilya mentions the construction of bridges and dams.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Ancient China has an extensive history of bridge construction, including cantilever bridges, rope bridges, and bridges built across floating boats.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The ancient Romans built many durable bridges using advanced engineering techniques.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Many Roman aqueducts – some still standing today – used a semicircular arch style.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Examples include the Alcántara Bridge in Spain and the Pont du Gard in France.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Romans used cement as a construction material, which could be mixed with small rocks to form concrete, or mixed with sand to form mortar to join bricks or stones.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some Roman cements, particularly those containing volcanic ash, were waterproof.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The enormous timber and stone Trajan's Bridge (c.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] 105 AD) crossed the Danube river and was over 900 meters (3,000 ft) long.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The oldest surviving stone bridge in China is the Anji Bridge, built from 595 to 605 AD during the Sui dynasty.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] This bridge is also historically significant as it is the world's oldest open-spandrel stone segmental arch bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Rope bridges, a simple type of suspension bridge, were used by the Inca civilization in the Andes mountains of South America prior to European colonization in the 16th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In Medieval Europe, bridge design capabilities declined after the fall of Rome, but revived in the High Middle Ages in France, England, and Italy with the construction of bridges like the Pont d'Avignon, bridges of the Durance river, and the Old London Bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Surviving examples include the Ponte Vecchio in Florence, the Old Exe Bridge, and the Monnow Bridge in Wales.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In 15th- and 16th-century Europe, the Renaissance brought a new emphasis on science and engineering.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Figures such as Galileo Galilei, Fausto Veranzio, and Andrea Palladio (author of *I quattro libri dell'architettura*) wrote treatises that applied a rigorous, analytic approach to architecture and building.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Their innovations included truss bridges and stone segmental arches, resulting in Florence's Ponte Santa Trinita, the Rialto Bridge in Venice, and Paris's Pont Neuf.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Military and commercial bridges were constructed in India by the Mughal administration.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Asante Empire in Africa built bridges over streams and rivers using tree trunks and beams.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the late 18th century, the design of arch bridges was revolutionized in Europe by Jean-Rodolphe Perronet and John Rennie.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] They designed arches that were flatter than semicircular Roman arches, which yielded faster construction times, better water flow under the bridge, and slimmer piers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] These designs were used for the Pont de la Concorde and New London Bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] With the advent of the Industrial Revolution, iron became an important construction material for bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Both cast iron (which is strong under compression, but brittle) and wrought iron (which was more ductile and better under tension) were used for building bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Iron Bridge in England – made of cast iron and completed in 1781 – was the first major bridge made entirely of metal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Several long suspension bridges were built in the early 19th century using iron eyebars (steel wire, vastly superior, became available later in the century).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The age of railways began in the 1820s, and led to major innovations in bridge design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Britain is representative of how railways influenced bridge-building in industrialized nations: led by designers Isambard Kingdom Brunel, Robert Stephenson, and Joseph Locke, British railway bridges steadily grew in size as the decades passed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Notable bridges of that era include the High Level Bridge (1849), Royal Border Bridge (1850), Britannia Bridge (1850), Royal Albert Bridge (1859), and Clifton Suspension Bridge (1864).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The number of railway bridges in Britain increased from 30,000 to 60,000 during the Railway Mania era.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Railway bridges primarily used masonry and stone arch designs, because those could withstand the tremendous loads imposed by trains, but iron beam designs (on masonry or stone piers) were also used.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The abundance of inexpensive lumber in North America led that continent to favor timber as a bridge material: using truss designs (for long spans) and trestle designs (for spanning deep ravines).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The mass production of steel in the late 19th century provided a new material for bridges, enabling lighter, stronger truss bridges and cantilever bridges; and steel wires replaced iron bars as the preferred material for suspension bridge cables.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Concrete – which was originally used within the Roman Empire – was improved with the invention of Portland cement in the early 19th century, and replaced stone and masonry as the primary material for bridge foundations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] When iron or steel is embedded in the concrete, as in reinforced concrete or prestressed concrete, it is a strong, inexpensive material that can be used for horizontal elements of beam bridges and box girder bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Throughout the 20th century, new bridges – by designer Othmar Ammann and others – repeatedly broke records for span distances, enabling transportation networks to cross increasingly wider rivers and valleys.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Cable-stayed bridges – which use cable-stays as the exclusive means of support – became a popular bridge design following World War II.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The late 20th century saw several major innovations in bridge design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Extradosed bridges were introduced and found widespread use, predominantly in Japan.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In China, concrete-filled steel tubes were adopted as a new approach to building arch bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Fiber-reinforced polymers – which do not suffer from the rust problems that plague steel – were used in bridges for many applications, such as beams, deck slabs, prestressing cables, wraps on the exterior of concrete elements, and internal reinforcing within concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the 21st century, a bridge span exceeded 2 kilometers (1.2 mi) for the first time with the construction of the 1915 Çanakkale Bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The purpose of any bridge is to traverse an obstacle.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge can provide support and transport for railways, cars, pedestrians, pipelines, cables, or any combination of these.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Aqueducts were developed early in human history, and carried water to towns and cities.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Canal systems sometimes include navigable aqueducts (also called *canal bridges*) to carry boats across a valley or ravine.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Until the early 19th century, most bridges were designed to carry pedestrians, horses, and horse-drawn carriages.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Following the invention of railways, many rail bridges were built; in Britain the number of bridges doubled during the railway-building boom in the mid-19th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Railway bridges have unique requirements because of the heavy loads they carry – a single locomotive can weigh 197 tonnes (217 short tons).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Railway bridges are designed to minimize deflection (bending under load), to maximize robustness (localize the damage caused by accidents), and to tolerate heavy impacts (sudden shocks from, for example, rail wheels striking an imperfection in the track).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] These requirements led railways to avoid curved bridges, suspension bridges, and cable-stayed bridges; instead, straight beam or truss bridges are commonly used.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The explosive growth of motorway networks in the 20th century required bridges to span ever longer distances to reach islands and cross valleys, along with the urban introduction of elevated railways and monorails.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] An important application of bridges is improving safety and traffic flow at traffic junctions where roads or railways cross at ground level.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Such intersections require vehicles to stop, and lead to slower traffic, wasted fuel, and higher incidence of collisions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] One technique to mitigate these issues is to build a bridge, enabling one of the roads to pass over the other: this process is known as grade separation.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Grade separation can be implemented at railway-road intersections or road-road intersections.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some bridges, known as footbridges, are devoted to pedestrian traffic.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] They range from simple boardwalks enabling passage over marshy land to elevated skybridges – including the Minneapolis Skyway System – which shield pedestrians from harsh winter weather.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] When used to cross roads in busy urban areas, footbridges are generally safer than crosswalks, but have been criticized by urbanists and disability advocates for inconveniencing pedestrians, hindering accessibility, diminishing the quality of city life, and perpetuating car dependency.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Military bridges are an important type of equipment in the field of military engineering.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] They perform a variety of wartime roles, namely quickly traversing obstacles in the midst of battle, or facilitating resupply behind front lines.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Military bridges can be categorized as *wet* bridges that rest on pontoon floats, and *dry* bridges that rest on piers, river banks, or anchorages.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A crude mechanism to cross a small ravine is to place a fascine (a large bundle of pipes or logs) into the ravine to enable vehicles to drive across.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Armoured vehicle-launched bridges are carried on purpose-built vehicles.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] These vehicles typically have the same cross-country performance as a tank, and can carry a bridge to an obstacle and deploy ("launch") the bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The UK's Chieftain vehicle could launch a 23-meter (75 ft) bridge – capable of supporting 54-tonne (60-short-ton) loads – in 3 minutes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Military bridges have found use in civilian applications.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Bailey bridge was originally invented in 1940 for use in World War II, but continues to be used in peacetime.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bailey bridges are used as small, permanent bridges, as well as temporary bridges used while a permanent bridge is being replaced or repaired.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] During wartime, bridges are often damaged by bombing or by combat engineers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges can be valuable targets because they are immobile, relatively easy to spot from the air, and damage to the bridge can disrupt the enemy's transportation network.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges have been targeted by artillery since antiquity, and the advent of newer technologies – specifically, aircraft and drones – has made bridges easier to attack.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Germany used the Stuka aircraft to perform dive-bomb attacks on bridges during World War II, and Ukraine damaged the Crimean Bridge with a drone attack in 2023.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some bridges accommodate uses other than transportation.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Pipeline bridges carry oil pipes or water pipes across valleys or rivers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Many historical bridges supported buildings, including shrines, factories, shops, restaurants, and houses.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Notable examples were the Old London Bridge and Ponte Vecchio.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some bridges built in Europe in the Middle Ages incorporated chapels into their design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the modern era, bridge-restaurants can be found at some highway rest areas; these support a restaurant or shops directly above the highway and are accessible to drivers moving in both directions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Examples include the Will Rogers Archway over the Oklahoma Turnpike and the several Illinois Tollway oasis locations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Nový Most bridge in Bratislava features a restaurant set atop its single tower.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Conservationists use wildlife bridges to reduce habitat fragmentation and animal-vehicle collisions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The first wildlife crossings were built in the 1950s, and these types of bridges are now used worldwide.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges are primarily classified by their basic structural design: arch, truss, cantilever, suspension, cable-stayed, or beam.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Several other terms can be used to designate various aspects of a bridge's form or design, including viaduct, trestle, and causeway.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The choice of bridge structure to use in a particular situation is based on many factors, including aesthetics, environment, cost, and purpose.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some bridge spans combine two types of basic structures; for instance, the Brooklyn Bridge is primarily a suspension structure, but also uses cable-stays.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some multi-span bridges – called *hybrid* bridges – use different basic structures for different spans.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Arch bridges consist of a curved arch, under compression, which supports the deck either above or below the arch.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The shape of the arch can be a semicircle, ellipse, pointed arch, or segment of a circle.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Arches exert a diagonal force at both ends, requiring strong supports or abutments to prevent the arch from spreading or collapsing.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Deck arch bridges hold the deck above the arch; tied-arch bridges suspend the deck below the arch; and through arch bridges position the deck through the middle of the arch.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A truss bridge is composed of multiple, connected triangular elements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The set of triangles form a rigid whole, which rests on the foundation at both ends, applying a vertical force downward.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The deck can be carried on top of the truss ("deck truss") or at the bottom of the truss ("through truss").
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Through trusses are useful when more clearance under the bridge is required; deck trusses permit oversize loads and do not interfere with overhead objects, such as electrical lines.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The individual bars can be made of iron or wood, but most modern truss bridges are made of steel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The horizontal bars along the top are usually in compression, and the horizontal bars along the bottom are usually in tension.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bars connecting the top and bottom may be in tension or compression, depending on the layout of the triangles.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Trusses typically have a span-to-depth ratio (the width of a structure divided by its height) ranging from 10 to 16, compared to beam bridges which typically have a ratio ranging from 20 to 30.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Trusses tend to be relatively stiff, and are commonly used for rail bridges which are required to carry very heavy loads.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Cantilever bridges consist of beams or trusses that are rigidly attached to a support (pier or anchorage) and extend horizontally from the support without additional supports.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In ancient Asia, cantilever bridges made of large rocks or timber were used to span small obstacles.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the 1880s, some early cantilever bridges were built from wrought iron, but steel became common starting in the late 19th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A balanced cantilever bridge consists of two connected cantilevers extending outward in opposite directions from a single central support.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Other cantilever bridges have two cantilevers, anchored at each end of the span, extending toward the center, and meeting in the center.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] *Cantilever construction* is a method of building a bridge superstructure, which can be utilized for arch and cable-stayed bridges, as well as cantilever bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In this technique, construction begins at a support (specifically a pier, abutment, or tower) and extends outwards across the obstacle, with no support from below.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Suspension bridges have large, curved cables attached to the tops of tall towers, and suspend the bridge deck from the cables.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the early 19th century, the first modern suspension bridges – such as the Jacob's Creek Bridge – were chain bridges that used iron bars rather than bundled wires for the cables.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] After steel wire became widely available, longer cables could be built by stringing hundreds of wires between the towers and bundling them, enabling suspension bridges to achieve spans 2 kilometers (1.2 miles) long.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] When the bridge crosses a river, stringing the wires across the large span is a complex process.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The cable of a suspension bridge assumes the shape of a catenary when initially suspended between the bridge towers; however, once the uniform load of the bridge deck is applied, the cable adopts a parabolic shape.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Shorter towers require a smaller sag in the cable, which increases the tension in the cable, and thus requires stronger towers and anchorages.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Cable-stayed bridges are similar to suspension bridges, but the cables that support the deck connect directly to the towers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The inclined cables may be arranged in a fan pattern or a harp pattern.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Modern cable-stayed bridges became popular after World War II, when the design was used for many new bridges in Germany.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] When traversing a wide obstacle, designers have a choice of suspension or cable-stayed structures.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Suspension bridges can achieve a longer span, but cable-stayed bridges use less cable for a given span size, do not require anchorages, and the deck can be readily built by cantilevering outward from the towers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Beam bridges are simple structures consisting of one or more parallel, horizontal beams or girders that span an obstacle.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A box girder bridge is a variant that is generally shallower than an I-beam equivalent, permitting shorter and lower approach roads to cross an obstacle of a given height.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Beam bridges are commonly used for both railways and roadways.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Beam bridges are often used for spans shorter than about 50 meters (160 ft); for longer spans, trusses or similar structures are generally more efficient.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The majority of beam bridges have a flat, horizontal bottom; but some have a bottom that arches upward, called *haunching*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Haunching looks more graceful than a flat bottom, and can provide greater clearance below the bridge, but it tends to be more costly because flat bottom beams are easier to build.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In addition to the basic bridge structures, there are many other forms of bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The following sections describe some of the more common forms, but are not an exhaustive list.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Movable bridges are designed so that all or part of the bridge deck can be moved, usually to permit tall traffic – such as tall boats or ships – to pass by.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Early movable bridges include drawbridges that pivoted at one end, and required a large amount of work to raise.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Adding counterweights on the pivot side of the drawbridge creates a bascule bridge, and makes moving the bridge easier and safer.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Swing bridges pivot horizontally around an anchor point on the bank of a canal, or sometimes from a pier in the middle of the water.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Lift bridges are raised vertically between two towers by cables passing over pulleys at the top of the towers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Notable movable bridges include El Ferdan Railway Bridge in Egypt, Erasmusbrug bascule in Rotterdam, and Limehouse Basin footbridge in London.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the modern era, designers sometimes create unusual movable bridges with the intention of establishing signature bridges for a town or locality.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Examples include the Puente de la Mujer swing bridge in Buenos Aires, the Gateshead Millennium – a rare example of a tilt bridge – over the River Tyne, and the Hörn Bridge in Germany.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] There are a variety of terms that describe long, multi-span bridges – including viaduct, trestle, continuous, and causeway.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The usage of the terms can overlap, but each has a specific focus.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Viaducts (carrying vehicles) and aqueducts (carrying water) are bridges crossing a valley or underpass, supported by multiple arches or piers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Romans built many aqueducts, some of which are still standing today.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Notable viaducts include Penponds Viaduct in England, Garabit Viaduct in France, Tunkhannock Viaduct in Pennsylvania, and Millau Viaduct in France.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A trestle bridge – commonly used in the 19th century for railway bridges – consists of multiple short spans supported by closely spaced structural elements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A trestle is similar to a viaduct, but viaducts typically have taller pier supports and longer spans.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A continuous truss bridge is a long, single truss that rests upon multiple supports.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A continuous truss bridge may use less material than a series of simple trusses because a continuous truss distributes live loads across all the spans (in contrast to a series of simple trusses, where each truss must be capable of supporting the entire live load).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Visually, a continuous truss looks similar to a cantilever bridge, but a continuous truss experiences hogging stresses at the supports and sagging stresses between the supports.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A causeway is a low road, usually crossing a bog, marsh, lake, or other body of water.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Many causeways are earthen embankments, but some are raised bridges, such as the 38.4-kilometer (23.9-mile) Lake Pontchartrain Causeway in Louisiana.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] An extradosed bridge combines features of a box girder bridge and a cable-stayed bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Visually, extradosed bridges can be distinguished from cable-stayed bridges because the tower height (above the deck) is relatively low: between seven and thirteen percent of the span width.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Extradosed bridges are appropriate for spans ranging from 100 meters (330 ft) to 250 meters (820 ft).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Unlike suspension bridges or cable-stayed bridges, the towers of an extradosed bridge often rest on the deck (rather than on a footing) and are solidly connected to the deck.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Because of the relatively flat angle of the cables, the cables of an extradosed bridge compress the deck horizontally, performing a function comparable to prestressing wires that are used within concrete girders.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Extradosed bridges may be appropriate in applications where the deck must have a shallow depth to maximize clearance under the bridge; or where towers must be relatively short to abide by aviation safety constraints.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A pontoon bridge, also known as a floating bridge, uses floats or shallow-draft boats to support a continuous deck for pedestrian or vehicle travel over water.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Pontoon bridges are typically used where waters are too deep to build piers, or as a mechanism to implement a movable swing bridge in a canal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] During the Second Persian invasion of Greece, Persian ruler Xerxes built a large pontoon bridge across the Hellespont, consisting of two parallel rows of 360 boats.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Several pontoon bridges are in use in the modern world.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Washington state in the US has several, including Hood Canal Bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In Norway, Nordhordland Bridge crosses a deep fjord by resting on floating concrete pontoons.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Many armies have pontoon bridges that can be rapidly deployed, including the PMP Floating Bridge, designed by the USSR.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The process for designing a new bridge typically goes through several stages, progressively refining the design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] An early step in the design process – sometimes called *conceptual design* – is to consider the multiple requirements that a bridge must satisfy.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Requirements that are directly related to function include lifespan, safety, climate, soil condition, traffic volume, the size and nature of the obstacle to be traversed, and clearance required for passage underneath.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Other constraints may include construction cost, maintenance cost, aesthetics, time available for construction, owner preference, and experience of the builders.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some bridge designs consider factors such as impact on the environment and wildlife, and the bridge's economic, social, and historic relationship to the local community.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] After the requirements of a bridge are established, a bridge designer uses structural analysis methods to identify candidate designs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Several designs may meet the requirements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The value engineering methodology can be used to select a final design from multiple alternatives.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] This methodology evaluates candidate designs based on weighted scores assigned to several different criteria, including cost, service life, durability, availability of resources, ease of construction, construction time, and maintenance cost.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] An important requirement considered during the design process is the service life, which is a specific number of years that the bridge is expected to remain in operation with routine maintenance (and without requiring major repairs).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] For example, wood bridge superstructures typically have a service life of 10 to 50 years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Concrete highway bridges can have service lives of 75 to 150 years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge design methodology incorporates the service life into the design process.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] One of the requirements a new bridge must satisfy is compliance with the local bridge design specifications and codes which – in some countries – may be legally binding requirements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In many countries, these specifications are developed and published by standards organizations that define acceptable bridge-building practices and designs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In Europe, the organization is the European Committee for Standardization, and the standards it publishes are the Eurocodes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the United States, the American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials (AASHTO) publishes the AASHTO LRFD Bridge Design Specifications.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Canada's bridge standard is the Canadian Highway Bridge Design Code, developed by the non-profit CSA Group.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Agencies that regulate aviation or waterways may also impose standards that dictate some aspects of a bridge design, such as requirements for aviation warning lights at the top of bridge towers, or navigational warning lights on bridge supports located in navigable waterways.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge's appearance is one of the factors considered during its design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Attractive bridges can have a positive impact on a community, and some bridges can even be considered as works of art.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridge designers that are known for emphasizing the visual appeal of their bridges include Thomas Telford, Gustave Eiffel, John Roebling, Robert Maillart, and Santiago Calatrava.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Qualities that influence the perceived attractiveness of a bridge include proportion, color, texture, order, refinement, environmental integration, and functionality.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The art historian Dan Cruickshank notes that bridges are regarded as manifestations of human imagination and ambition, and that many bridges transcend their original utilitarian role and become a work of art.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge designer can select from a wide variety of materials, including wood, brick, rope, stone, iron, steel, and concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge made from two or more distinct materials (for example, steel and concrete) is known as a composite bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some of the largest arch bridges are composite, because they are made from concrete and steel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Wood is an inexpensive renewable resource with a high strength-to-weight ratio, but it is rarely used for modern roadway bridges because it is prone to degradation from the environment, and is much weaker than steel or concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Wood is primarily used in beam or truss bridges including covered bridges, and is also used to build large trestle bridges for railways.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] When wood is used, it is often in the form of glued laminated timber.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Masonry includes stone and brick, and is suitable only for elements of a bridge that are under compression (as opposed to tension), therefore, masonry is limited to structures such as arches or foundations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In the 20th century, large masonry bridges – although superseded by concrete in the West – continued to be built in China.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Iron – including cast iron and wrought iron – was used extensively from the late 18th century to late 19th century, primarily for arch and truss structures.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Iron is relatively brittle, and has been replaced by steel for all but ornamental uses.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Steel is one of the most common materials used in modern bridges because it is strong in both compression and tension.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Steel was made in small quantities in antiquity, but became widely available in the late 19th century following invention of new smelting processes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Truss bridges and beam bridges are often made of steel, and steel wires are an essential component of virtually all suspension bridges and cable-stayed bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Steel is a critical component in concrete bridges, because steel reinforcing bars or steel prestressed cables must be embedded within concrete to make it sufficiently strong.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Steel bridges are more expensive than comparable concrete bridges, but they are much lighter (for the same strength), faster to build, and offer more flexibility during construction and repair.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Concrete is commonly used in modern bridges, and many roadway bridges are built primarily with a reinforced concrete beam structure, often of the box girder variety.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The shape of concrete elements is determined by the formwork (mold) into which the concrete is poured (cast): the concrete will adopt the shape of the formwork as it cures.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Beams can be precast offsite and transported to the bridge site, or cast in place.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges use concrete that contains embedded steel reinforcing bars – placed within the concrete when it is initially poured – which greatly increase the strength.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Concrete is a strong and inexpensive material, but is brittle and can crack when in tension.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] If concrete is used in elements that may experience tension, prestressed cables are usually embedded within the concrete and tightened, which compresses the concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] When a horizontal beam is placed into the bridge and carries a load, the undesirable tension (produced by the tendency of the beam to sag) is counteracted by the compression from the prestressed cables.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The prestressed cables can be pre-tensioned (stretched before – and while – the concrete cures); or post-tensioned (placed within tubes in the concrete, and tightened after the concrete cures).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Designers may choose to use a double-deck design (also known as double-decked or double-decker), that carries two decks on top of each other.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] This technique can be used to increase the amount of traffic a bridge can carry; or when the location constrains the size of the bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Double-deck bridges also permit two different kinds of traffic to be safely carried.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] For example, motor vehicles can be separated from pedestrians or railways.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some double-deck bridges carry rail on one deck, and vehicles on the other deck.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] An early example was the Niagara Falls Suspension Bridge, and a modern example is the Dom Luís I Bridge in Portugal.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The George Washington Bridge in New York carries 14 motor vehicle lanes (eight above, six below), and is the world's busiest bridge, carrying over 100 million vehicles annually.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A bridge design must accommodate all loads and forces that the bridge might reasonably experience.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The totality of the forces that the bridge must tolerate is the structural load, which is often divided into three components: dead load, live load, and environmental load.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The dead load is the weight of the bridge itself.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The live load is all forces and vibrations caused by traffic passing over the bridge, including weight, braking, and acceleration.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The environmental load encompasses all forces applied by the bridge's surroundings, including weather, earthquakes, mudslides, water currents, flooding, soil subsidence, frost heaving, temperature fluctuations, and collisions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] For sporadic events like floods, earthquakes, collisions, and hurricanes, bridge designers select a maximum severity that the design must accommodate.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The severity is based on the return period, which is average time between events of a given magnitude.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Return periods range from 10 to 2,500 years, depending on type of event and the country in which the bridge is located.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Longer return periods are used for bridges that are a critical part of the transportation infrastructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] For example, if the bridge is a key lifeline in case of emergencies, the designer may utilize relatively long return period, for instance, 2,000 years; in this example, the design must endure the strongest storm that is expected to happen once every 2,000 years.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The load forces acting on a bridge cause the components of the bridge to become stressed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Stress is a measure of the internal force experienced within a material.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Strain is a measure of how much a bridge component bends, stretches, or twists in response to stress.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some strain (bending or twisting) may be acceptable in a bridge component if the material is elastic.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] For example, steel can tolerate some stretching or bending without failing.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] In contrast, concrete is inelastic, and the change in its shape when stressed is negligible (until the stress becomes excessive and the concrete fails).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A critical phase of the design process is calculating the maximum stress that each bridge component will experience, and selecting an appropriate design and size for the components to ensure they will safely tolerate the loads on the bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Stresses are categorized based on the nature of the force that causes the stress, namely: compression, tension, shear, and torsion.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Compression forces compact a component by pushing inward (for example, as felt by a bridge foundation when a heavy tower is resting on it).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Tension is a stretching force experienced by a component when pulled (for example by the cables of a suspension bridge).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Shear is a sliding force experienced by a component when two offset external forces are applied in opposite directions (for example, during an earthquake when the upper part of a structure is pulled north, and the lower part is pulled south).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The bridge design process typically employs structural analysis methods that divide the bridge into smaller components, and analyze the components individually, subject to certain constraints.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] A proposed bridge design is then usually modeled with formulas or computer applications.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The models incorporate the loads the bridge will experience, calculate the stresses in the bridge, and provide data to the designer indicating whether the design meets the required design goals.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] To ensure that a proposed bridge design is sufficiently strong to endure foreseeable stresses, many bridge designers use limit state design methodologies (used in Europe and China) or Load and Resistance Factor Design (LRFD) methodologies (used in US).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Many loads imposed on a bridge – wind, earthquakes, and vehicular traffic – can cause a bridge to experience irregular or periodic forces, which may cause bridge components to vibrate or oscillate.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Some bridge components have inherent resonant frequencies to which they are particularly susceptible, and vibrations near those frequencies can cause very large stresses.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Winds can produce a variety of vibrational forces on a bridge, including flutter, galloping, and vortex shedding.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Considering wind forces during the design process is especially important for long, slender bridges (typically suspension or cable-stayed bridges).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] If resonance issues are identified in the design process, they must be mitigated.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Common techniques to address vibration include increasing the rigidity of the bridge deck by adding trusses and adding dampers to cables and towers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Neglecting to account for vibrations and oscillations can lead to bridge failure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] The Tacoma Narrows Bridge collapsed in 1940 in winds of 68 km/h (42 mph), even though the bridge was designed to withstand winds up to 206 km/h (128 mph).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Investigations revealed that the designer failed to account for wind-induced flutter and resonant vibrations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] Bridges can suffer severe damage when subjected to earthquake ground motions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] During a seismic event, several phenomena can occur, such as long-period velocity pulses, shear cracks, large ground motions, vertical accelerations, and soil liquefaction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] To mitigate risks, earthquake engineers study seismic data to classify and quantify the motions experienced by bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p01] These studies are used by governments to create and revise design standards that specify the types of seismic movements that new bridges must withstand.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The structural elements of a bridge are generally divided into the substructure and the superstructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The substructure consists of the lower portions of the bridge, including the footings, abutments, piers, pilings, anchorages, and bearings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The superstructure rests upon the substructure, and consists of the deck, trusses, arches, towers, cables, beams, and girders.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Construction of a bridge is typically managed by construction engineers, who are responsible for planning and supervising the construction process.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Important aspects of this role include budgeting, scheduling, periodically conducting formal design reviews, and communicating with the bridge designers to interpret and update the design plans.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] When an existing bridge is being replaced or refurbished, the impact on traffic flow can have a detrimental effect on residents and services.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Accelerated bridge construction processes – that focus on using pre-fabricated components and a rapid timetable – may be used to mitigate the impacts.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The forces experienced by a bridge during construction can be larger or have a different nature than the forces it will experience after completion.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The bridge design process typically focuses on the strength of the fully completed bridge, but it should also consider the unusual stresses that individual elements will experience during construction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Special techniques may be required during construction to avoid excessive stresses, such as temporary supports under the bridge, temporary bracing or reinforcement, or permanently strengthening specific elements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] For instance, when a cable-stayed bridge with concrete towers is complete, the towers will experience desirable compression forces from the heavy load of the cables; but during construction, without that load, the towers may experience undesirable tension forces caused by lateral winds.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Construction of all bridge types begins by creating the substructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The first elements built are usually the footings and abutments, which are typically large blocks of reinforced concrete, entirely or partially buried underground.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The footings and abutments support the entire weight of the bridge, and transfer the weight to the subsoil.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Based on their height-to-width ratio, footings are categorized as: shallow (height is less than width) or deep (height is greater than width).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] If the subsoil cannot support the load placed on the footings, pilings must first be driven below the footings: pilings are long structures – made of wood, steel, or concrete – placed vertically below footings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some pilings reach down and rest on bedrock; others rely on friction to prevent the footing from sinking lower.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Abutments are usually located at the ends of a bridge deck, where it reaches the subsoil.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] They direct the weight into the subsoil, either vertically or diagonally.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Abutments may also act as retaining walls, keeping the subsoil under the approach road from eroding.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] After footings for the piers have been created, the piers and pier caps are built to complete the substructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Suspension bridges usually require anchorages, which are large reinforced concrete blocks solidly anchored into the earth – they must be exceptionally heavy and tied into the subsoil because they must withstand the lateral pull of the large cables that hold the entire deck and live load.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] When bridge supports (piers or towers) are built in a river, lake, or ocean, special technologies must be utilized.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Caissons can be used to provide a workspace while constructing the submerged portion of the supports.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] A caisson is a large, watertight, hollow structure, open on the bottom.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] It is usually sunk to the bottom of the water and workers can work inside, preparing the ground for the footings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] When excavation is complete, a caisson is typically filled with concrete to create all or part of the footing.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Air pressure inside a sealed caisson must be kept high to prevent water from seeping in.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Workers, if they do not properly decompress when exiting the caisson, can get decompression sickness.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Early bridge builders did not understand decompression, and deaths were common: thirteen workers died from decompression sickness when building the Eads Bridge (completed in 1874).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Another approach for constructing foundations in water is a box caisson, which is a large steel or concrete box, open on top, which is towed by tugboats to the bridge site, then sunk to the bottom and filled with concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The Akashi Kaikyo suspension bridge used box caissons for its two foundations – each 70 meters (230 ft) tall and 80 meters (260 ft) in diameter.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The caissons were sunk to the bottom in water 60 meters (200 ft) deep, and each was filled with 355,000 cubic meters of concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The foundations rest directly on the ocean bottom, without pilings or footings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] An alternative to a caisson is a cofferdam, which is a temporary dam surrounding the support location, open on top, where workers may work while constructing the footings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bearings are often placed between the superstructure and the substructure at the points of contact.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bearings are mechanical devices that enable small movements – which may result from thermal expansion and contraction, material creep, or minor seismic events.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Without bearings, the bridge structure may be damaged when such movements occur.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bearings can be selected to permit small rotational or slipping movements in a specific direction, without permitting movements in other directions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Types of bearings used on bridges include hinge bearings, roller bearings, rocker bearings, sliding bearings, spring bearings, and elastomeric bearings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] After the substructure is complete, the superstructure is built, resting on the substructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Beam bridge superstructures may be built in place, or fabricated off-site (precast) and transported to the bridge site.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Precast beams may be placed atop the supports by a crane or gantry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] If the span crosses a deep ravine, a technique known as launching may be used: the beams and deck are assembled on the approach road, then pushed horizontally across the obstacle.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Arch bridge superstructure construction methods depend on the material.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Concrete or stone arches use a temporary wood structure known as falsework or centering to support the arch while it is built.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some steel arch bridges are constructed with falsework, but others use cantilevering to build both halves out from the abutments.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Cantilever bridge superstructures are usually built incrementally by proceeding outward from anchorages or piers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Most cantilever superstructures can be built without temporary support piers, as the bridge can support itself as it extends outward.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] A similar process is used for steel or concrete cantilevers: prefabricated sections may be positioned at ground (or water) level and hoisted into place with a gantry, or may be transported horizontally along the previously completed portion of the cantilever.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Concrete cantilevers require steel prestressing cables to be passed through tubes within each section and tightened, which will put the concrete into compression.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Truss bridges are built using a variety of methods, including piece-by-piece, cantilevering, or falsework.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Cable-stayed bridge superstructures begin with the construction of one or more towers which rest directly on footings that are part of the substructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The deck is constructed in pieces beginning at the towers and moving outward.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The pieces can be put into place by hoisting, supporting from below, launching, or cantilevering from the portion of the deck that has been assembled.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] As each piece of the deck is added, it is connected to towers with steel cables, and the cables are tightened to take the load of the deck.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Suspension bridge superstructure construction usually begins with the towers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The towers may be steel or concrete, and rest directly on footings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The large cables are created by hauling a large pulley back and forth across the span, stringing multiple wires between the anchorages in each pass, in a process termed *spinning*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] After the wires are spun, they are bundled together to form the cables.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The cables are securely fastened to the anchorages at both ends.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Vertical wires called *hangers* are suspended from the cables, then small sections of the deck are attached to the hangers, and the sections are attached to each other.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Towers, made of either concrete or steel, are an important component of the superstructure of cable-stayed bridges and suspension bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Concrete is generally suitable for towers up to about 250 meters (820 ft) tall, whereas steel towers can be taller.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Towers support the bridge cables, which hold the weight of the deck and the traffic.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Most of the load imposed on a tower is applied vertically downward on the tower, rather than sideways.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Towers experience a compression stress, in contrast to cables, which experience a tension stress.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] There are two mechanisms used to attach a cable to a tower: saddles or anchors.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Saddles are curved structures which allow a cable to pass through (or over the top of) a tower.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Saddles are often used in suspension bridges, and anchors are often used in cable-stayed bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Steel cables are an element of both cable-stayed bridges and suspension bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Cables are made of one or more strands, and each strand consists of multiple wires.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] A wire is a thin, flexible piece of solid steel, of higher tensile strength than normal steel, and with a diameter of 3mm to 7mm.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Cables are typically constructed at the bridge site by unspooling wires or strands from large reels.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Large suspension bridges may use cables that are over 1 meter (3 ft 3 in) in diameter and weigh over 20,000 tonnes (44,092,450 lb).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Before building the cables of a suspension bridge, temporary catwalks must be constructed to support the wires while they are drawn across the span and over the tops of the towers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] There are two approaches to pulling the wires across the span: the air spinning method (in which individual wires are carried across by pulleys); and the prefabricated strand method (in which entire strands are pulled across).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The air spinning method was used for all suspension bridges until the prefabricated strand method was invented in the 1960s.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] After 300 to 500 wires are pulled, aluminum bands are used to bundle them into strands.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The wires within a strand may be parallel, or they may wrap around each other in a twisted (spiral) pattern.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Air spinning always produces strands that contain parallel wires.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The prefabricated strand method can utilize strands with parallel or twisted wires.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The deck of a bridge is the flat, horizontal surface that extends across the full span of a bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Decks generally rest on beams or box girders.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] When a deck is rigidly attached to its supporting beams or girders, they function together as a single structure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Two common types of decks are concrete decks and orthotropic steel decks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Concrete decks are flat slabs of reinforced concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The slabs may precast off-site, or cast-in-place by pouring concrete into forms on the bridge superstructure.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Orthotropic steel decks consist of a flat steel plate, coated with a wearing surface.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Numerous small steel ribs are welded to the underside of the top plate, running in the direction of the bridge roadway.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Below the ribs are steel floor beams, placed crosswise to the ribs.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Orthotropic steel decks are more expensive than concrete steel decks, but weigh less.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] They are useful in applications where weight is critical, a thin deck is required, or the environment is subject to earthquakes or extreme cold weather.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Many decks have a wearing surface on top, which is a layer of material designed to be periodically replaced after it is worn away by vehicular traffic.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Wearing surfaces are typically made of aggregate (small rocks) mixed with a binder such as asphalt, polyurethane, epoxy resins, or polyester.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Railway bridge decks are categorized as open decks (the ties rest directly on beams or girders, with air gaps between) and ballast decks (the ties rest on ballast rocks, and the ballast rests on a deck slab).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Constructing the deck (and its supporting beams or girders) can be difficult when the bridge is over water or a deep valley.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] A variety of techniques are available, and the choice depends on the topography of the site, the deck material (concrete or steel), traffic or obstacles under the bridge, and whether sections can be built off-site and transported to the bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] To achieve the designed service life, a bridge must be protected from deterioration by incorporating certain features into the design.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges can deteriorate due to a variety of causes, including rust, corrosion, chemical actions, and mechanical abrasion.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Deterioration is sometimes visible as rust on steel components, or cracks and spalling in concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Deterioration can be slowed with various measures, primarily aimed at excluding water and oxygen from the bridge elements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Techniques to prevent water-based damage include drainage systems, waterproofing membranes (such as polymer films), and eliminating expansion joints.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Concrete bridge elements can be protected with waterproof seals and coatings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Reinforcing steel within concrete can be protected by using high-quality concrete and increasing the thickness of the concrete surrounding the steel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Steel elements of a bridge can be protected by paints or by galvanizing with zinc.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Paint can be avoided entirely for steel members by using stainless steel or weathering steel (a steel alloy that eliminates the need for paint, by forming a protective outer layer of rust).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridge scour is a potentially serious problem when bridge footings are located in water.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Currents in the water can cause the sand and rocks around and below the footings to wash away over time.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] This effect can be mitigated by placing a cofferdam around the footings, or surrounding the footings with large, carefully placed rocks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Suspension bridges and cable-stayed bridges have large cables containing hundreds of steel wires.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Several techniques are used to minimize corrosion inside the cables, including wrapping the cables with galvanized wire, injecting the cables with grout or epoxy, using interlocking S-profile wires, and circulating dry air through the interior of the cable.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges with supports in navigable waterways are designed to withstand ship strikes up to a specific, predefined magnitude.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In addition to waterway markings and pilot warning systems, bridge supports in water may be surrounded by physical protections such as fenders, pilings, or small artificial islands.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] After a bridge is completed and becomes operational, management processes are employed to ensure that it remains open to traffic, avoids safety incidents, and achieves its intended lifespan.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] These processes – collectively referred to as *bridge management* – include technical activities – namely, maintenance, inspection, monitoring, and testing.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In addition to technical tasks, management encompasses planning, budgeting, and prioritization of maintenance activities.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridge managers use bridge management systems and life-cycle cost analysis methodologies to manage a bridge and estimate the maintenance costs of a bridge throughout its lifetime.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Annual maintenance costs increase as the bridge ages and degrades.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Maintenance activities seek to prolong the life of the bridge, reduce lifecycle costs, and ensure the safety of the community.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Maintenance tasks can be categorized as corrective tasks and preventive tasks.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Corrective tasks are implemented in response to unexpected issues that arise, for example, repairing structural elements (piers, beams, girders, towers, or cables) and replacing bearings.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Preventive tasks include washing, painting, lubricating bearings, sealing the deck, filling cracks, removing snow, filling potholes, and repairing minor issues with structures and electrical fixtures.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some preventive tasks are performed on a periodic schedule.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] An important part of maintenance is inspecting a bridge for damage or degradation, and taking steps to mitigate any issues detected.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Degradation can come from environmental sources, including expansion/contraction from freeze/thaw cycles, rain, oxidation of steel, and sea spray.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Human activities may also cause damage, for example: vehicular traffic, mechanical abrasion, poor bridge design, and improper repair procedures.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some countries mandate periodic inspection schedules, for example, routine inspections every 24 months, or inspecting underwater foundations for scouring every 60 months.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Relying solely on visual inspection to assess degradation of a bridge can be unreliable, so inspectors use a variety of nondestructive testing techniques.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] These techniques include hammer strike tests, ultrasonic pulse velocity tests, seismic tomography, and ground penetrating radar.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Various electrical tests that assess permeability and resistance can give insight into the condition of surface concrete.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] X-rays can be passed through concrete to obtain data about concrete density and condition.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Videography using slender probes can be used where access is available.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Measurements of the state of a bridge may be made automatically and periodically using structural health monitoring (SHM) technologies.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some testing – termed destructive testing – requires removing samples from the bridge and taking them to a laboratory for analysis with microscopes, sonic devices, or X-ray diffraction.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Destructive testing is performed by removing cores drilled from concrete, or a small piece of steel wire cut from a cable.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Funding for bridge construction and operation comes from a variety of sources, including fuel taxes, annual vehicle registration fees, tolls, congestion fees, and usage fees based on satellite tracking.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some bridges – particularly in developing countries – are financed by international sources including the World Bank or China's Belt and Road Initiative.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Toll systems are generally an inefficient mechanism for collecting funding, particularly when tollbooths are used, because they are expensive to build and manage.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Tollbooths can slow down traffic and interfere with the construction of entry or exit points.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The cost of building a bridge is typically borne by government agencies, but since 1990 an increasing number of bridges are built and paid for by private companies using a public–private partnership (PPP) agreement.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In a PPP project, the government grants the right to build the bridge to a company, and the company recoups its expenses by collecting tolls for a fixed period of time.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] At the end of the period, the bridge is transferred to government ownership, and the government may choose to continue to charge tolls or not.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Notable bridges constructed with a PPP model include the Queen Elizabeth II Bridge (built in 1991, toll collection period 20 years) and the Second Severn Crossing (built in 1996, toll collection period 30 years).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridge failures are of special importance to structural engineers, because the analyses of the failures provide lessons learned that serve to improve design and construction processes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridge failures have a variety of causes, which can be categorized as natural factors (flood, scour, earthquake, landslide, and wind) and human factors (improper design and construction method, collision, overloading, fire, corrosion, and lack of inspection and maintenance).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Over time, bridge failures have led to significant improvements in bridge design, construction, and maintenance practices.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Before the advent of bridge engineering procedures based on rigorous, scientific principles, bridges frequently failed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Failures were most common in the mid-19th century, when the rapidly expanding railway networks were building hundreds of new bridges every year around the globe.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In the United States, 40 bridges per year failed in the 1870s, amounting to 25% of all bridges built in that decade.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In the modern era, in spite of advances in bridge engineering methodologies, bridge failures continue to occur regularly.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In Australia, the King Street Bridge collapsed in 1962, a year after opening, due to improper welding techniques.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In Palau, the Koror–Babeldaob Bridge collapsed in 1996, three months after a repair operation made major changes to the bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In 1998, the Turag-Bhakurta Bridge in Bangladesh collapsed due to river waters scouring away the soil around the bridge supports.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The Millennium Bridge in London opened in 2000, but closed two days later due to excessive swaying.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] It did not open until two years later – after dampers were installed.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] About half of all bridge failures in the early 21st century in the US were due to flood damage or scouring (water currents undermining the bridge supports).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Many bridges – known as *signature bridges* – are strongly identified with a particular community.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Large suspension bridges, in particular, are often regarded as iconic landmarks that symbolize the cities in which they are located.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Notable examples include the Brooklyn Bridge in New York; the Golden Gate Bridge in San Francisco; the Clifton Suspension Bridge in Bristol; and the Széchenyi Chain Bridge in Budapest.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some visually impressive bridges, such as the Dagu Bridge in China, are designed with the express goal of creating a landmark for the host city.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges can have significant impacts – both positive and negative – on a community's environment, society, and economy.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] During the bridge design process, these effects may be modeled with life cycle sustainability assessment or building information modeling, and the results can be used to adjust the bridge's design to improve its effect on the environment, society, and economy.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Positive effects of a new bridge can include shorter transport times, employment opportunities, improvements to social equity, improved productivity, and increases to the gross domestic product (GDP).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Construction of a new bridge can increase wages in the surrounding region, but can also increase income inequity between genders (men see larger wage gains than women) and between education levels (higher-educated persons see more gains than lower-educated persons).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In locales where flooding is common, bridges can increase overall income by providing reliable crossings across rivers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In underdeveloped regions with mountainous topography, construction of bridges that cross deep valleys can bring major benefits to the communities they connect.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Without bridges, such areas often have a core region that is more prosperous, surrounded by less developed peripheral regions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Building bridges over deep valleys can reduce developmental disparities between areas, as well as generate economic development, and improve accessibility to goods and services.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Global warming can be exacerbated by the creation of a new bridge, because the production of concrete significantly contributes to the greenhouse effect.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Although bridges can boost the economy of the surrounding region, they also increase environmental pollution proportionally.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Corruption endemic in the construction industry (including bridge building) can produce negative societal and economic consequences.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges that carry highways can result in increased vehicular collisions, which have economic costs (medical care and lost productivity) averaging over €14,000 each.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Suicides are sometimes carried out by jumping off bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] This method can account for 20% to 70% of suicides in urban areas with access to tall bridges.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In some regions, suicide by jumping disproportionately affects young adults, who tend to have lower inhibitory control.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Specific bridges can gain notoriety and attract persons experiencing a suicidal crisis, which creates a feedback loop.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] High-risk bridges often have suicide prevention barriers installed, which dramatically decrease the suicide rate on the bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Installing barriers on a high-risk bridge generally reduces the jumping suicide rate in a region, although in some instances, other bridges become substitutes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The profession of civil engineering – which includes the discipline of bridge building – began to be formalized in the 18th century when a school of engineering was created in France within the Corps des Ponts et Chaussées at the École de Paris, under the direction of Jacques Gabriel.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In 1747 the first school dedicated to bridge building was founded: the École Nationale des Ponts et Chaussées led by French engineers Daniel-Charles Trudaine and Jean-Rodolphe Perronet.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] The first professional organization focused on civil engineering was the Institution of Civil Engineers founded in 1818 in the UK, initially led by Thomas Telford.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In the modern era, bridge engineering is regulated by national organizations, such as the National Council of Examiners for Engineering and Surveying (US), the Canadian Council of Professional Engineers (Canada), and the Engineering Council (UK).
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In many countries, bridge engineers must be licensed or meet minimal educational requirements.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Some countries require engineers to pass qualification examinations, for example, in the US engineers must pass the Fundamentals of Engineering exam followed by the Principles and Practice of Engineering exam.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In Poland, bridge engineers are required to obtain certification by accumulating several years of experience under a senior engineer, and passing an exam administered by the Polish Chamber of Civil Engineers.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] International cooperation in the field of engineering is facilitated by the World Federation of Engineering Organizations.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges occur extensively in art, legend, and literature, often employed as metaphors or symbols of human accomplishment, lifespan, or experience.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In Norse mythology, the home of the gods – Asgard – is connected to the earth by Bifröst, a rainbow bridge.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Many bridges in Europe are named *Devil's Bridge*, and in some cases have folkloric stories that explain why the bridge is associated with the devil.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bénézet lifted a huge boulder to begin construction of the Pont Saint-Bénézet bridge, and went on to found the apocryphal Bridge-Building Brotherhood.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges feature prominently in paintings – often in the background – as in the *Mona Lisa*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In the modern era, bridges continue to feature prominently in culture.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Bridges are often the setting for pageants, celebrations, and processions.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Authors have used bridges as the centerpiece of novels, notably *The Bridge on the Drina* by Ivo Andrić and Thornton Wilder's *The Bridge of San Luis Rey*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] British poet Philip Larkin, inspired by the construction of the Humber Bridge near his home, wrote "Bridge for the Living" in 1981.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Neighboring nations have chosen to designate some shared bridges as *friendship bridges* or *peace bridges*.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] In 1996, the European Commission held a competition to select art for the euro banknotes.
[src:horseley-ironworks/bridge-p02] Robert Kalina, an Austrian designer, won with a set of illustrations of bridges, chosen because they symbolize links between states in the union and paths to the future.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The **Horseley Ironworks** (sometimes spelled **Horsley**) was a major ironworks in the Tipton area in the county of Staffordshire, now the West Midlands, England.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] Founded by Aaron Manby, it is most famous for constructing the first iron steamer, *The Aaron Manby*, in 1821.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] She was only the first of a number of steamboats built on the "knock-down" principle.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The ironworks have also been responsible for the manufacture of numerous canal and railway bridges of the 19th century.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The ironworks were built near the Toll End Communication Canal on the Horseley estate, which had been sold by their owner at the turn of the 19th century due to demand from engineers wishing to profit on the construction of the BCN Main Line through the estate.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The date when the ironworks were constructed is unknown but is believed to have been by 1815.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] Industry in the area prospered and the location retained the name of the Horseley estate as shown in an 1822 survey of the area.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] With the increasing popularity of canals, the ironworks quickly became popular for manufacturing canal bridges, mainly in the local vicinity.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] Canal bridges made by the ironworks include the Engine Arm Aqueduct (1825), two roving bridges at Smethwick Junction (1828), Galton Bridge (1829), and Braunston Towpath Bridges (1830).
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] By the end of the canal construction era, Horseley Ironworks had emerged as one of the most prolific manufacturers of canal bridges in the West Midlands region, especially in Birmingham.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] This was a result of their signature bridge design which had become popular amongst canal constructors.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The design has been replicated more recently, for example in Birmingham during the regeneration of Gas Street Basin where Worcester Bar is linked to Gas Street.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] Horseley Ironworks were also responsible for manufacturing in the railway industry.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] Railway bridges constructed included that of the viaduct for the London and Birmingham to Holyhead railway at Shifnal, Shropshire which was cast in 1848.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] As well as manufacturing bridges, they also produced locomotives.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The company also manufactured construction steelwork for the pier of Ryde, the Palace Theatre in London, Rugby railway station, a seaplane hangar in Las Palmas and the Dome of Discovery at the 1951 Festival of Britain.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] People who have worked for the iron foundry include Charles Manby, the son of Aaron Manby, James Thomson, William Johnson and Richard Roberts.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The firm moved in 1865 to a site on the now defunct Dixon's Branch, off the BCN New Main Line (Island Line), near the South Staffordshire Railway line.
[src:horseley-ironworks/horseley-ironworks] The factory survived under a succession of owners until 1991, when it was closed down and subsequently redeveloped as a housing estate.
